Note: =====================================================================
Note: SMOOTH MANIFOLD OPERATIONS
Note: =====================================================================

Process called "create_smooth_manifold" that takes dimension as Integer, atlas as Dictionary[String, SmoothChart] returns SmoothManifold:
    Note: Create smooth manifold with specified dimension and smooth atlas
    Note: Validates atlas compatibility and constructs transition functions
    
    Note: Validate dimension
    If dimension <= 0:
        Throw Errors.InvalidArgument with "Manifold dimension must be positive"
    
    Note: Validate atlas
    If atlas.size() == 0:
        Throw Errors.InvalidArgument with "Atlas must contain at least one chart"
    
    Note: Check dimension consistency across charts
    For each chart_id in atlas.keys():
        Let chart be atlas.get(chart_id)
        If chart.coordinate_map.size() == 0:
            Throw Errors.InvalidArgument with "Chart must have coordinate mappings"
    
    Note: Compute transition functions between overlapping charts
    Let transition_functions be Collections.Map[Tuple[String, String], String]()
    
    For each chart_i_id in atlas.keys():
        For each chart_j_id in atlas.keys():
            If chart_i_id != chart_j_id:
                Let chart_i be atlas.get(chart_i_id)
                Let chart_j be atlas.get(chart_j_id)
                
                Note: Check for chart overlap (simplified heuristic)
                Let has_overlap be false
                For each point_id in chart_i.chart_domain:
                    If chart_j.chart_domain.contains(point_id):
                        Set has_overlap to true
                        Break
                
                If has_overlap:
                    Note: Create transition function representation (symbolic)
                    Let transition_key be Tuple.create(chart_i_id, chart_j_id)
                    Let transition_expr be "transition_" + chart_i_id + "_to_" + chart_j_id
                    transition_functions.put(transition_key, transition_expr)
    
    Note: Determine manifold type based on structure
    Let manifold_type be "general"
    If dimension == 1:
        Set manifold_type to "curve"
    Otherwise If dimension == 2:
        Set manifold_type to "surface"
    Otherwise If dimension >= 3:
        Set manifold_type to "higher_dimensional"
    
    Let manifold be SmoothManifold {
        dimension: dimension,
        smooth_atlas: atlas,
        transition_functions: transition_functions,
        manifold_type: manifold_type,
        boundary_manifold: null
    }
    
    Return manifold

Process called "verify_smooth_structure" that takes manifold as SmoothManifold returns Boolean:
    Note: Verify smooth structure by checking compatibility of charts and transition maps
    Note: Checks C∞ compatibility conditions for overlapping charts
    
    Note: Check basic manifold properties
    If manifold.dimension <= 0:
        Return false
    
    If manifold.smooth_atlas.size() == 0:
        Return false
    
    Note: Verify each chart has valid coordinate mappings
    For each chart_id in manifold.smooth_atlas.keys():
        Let chart be manifold.smooth_atlas.get(chart_id)
        
        Note: Check chart domain is non-empty
        If chart.chart_domain.size() == 0:
            Return false
        
        Note: Verify coordinate map consistency
        If chart.coordinate_map.size() == 0:
            Return false
        
        Note: Check smoothness class
        If chart.smoothness_class != "C_infinity" and chart.smoothness_class != "smooth":
            Return false
    
    Note: Verify transition function compatibility
    For each transition_key in manifold.transition_functions.keys():
        Let chart_i_id be transition_key.first()
        Let chart_j_id be transition_key.second()
        
        Note: Check that both charts exist
        If manifold.smooth_atlas.get(chart_i_id) == null:
            Return false
        If manifold.smooth_atlas.get(chart_j_id) == null:
            Return false
        
        Let chart_i be manifold.smooth_atlas.get(chart_i_id)
        Let chart_j be manifold.smooth_atlas.get(chart_j_id)
        
        Note: Verify charts actually overlap
        Let overlap_exists be false
        For each point in chart_i.chart_domain:
            If chart_j.chart_domain.contains(point):
                Set overlap_exists to true
                Break
        
        If overlap_exists == false:
            Return false
    
    Note: Check reciprocal transition functions exist
    For each transition_key in manifold.transition_functions.keys():
        Let chart_i_id be transition_key.first()
        Let chart_j_id be transition_key.second()
        Let reciprocal_key be Tuple.create(chart_j_id, chart_i_id)
        
        If manifold.transition_functions.get(reciprocal_key) == null:
            Return false
    
    Note: Verify atlas covers manifold (heuristic check)
    Let total_coverage be 0
    For each chart_id in manifold.smooth_atlas.keys():
        Let chart be manifold.smooth_atlas.get(chart_id)
        Set total_coverage to total_coverage + chart.chart_domain.size()
    
    If total_coverage == 0:
        Return false
    
    Note: All checks passed - smooth structure is valid
    Return true

Process called "construct_tangent_bundle" that takes manifold as SmoothManifold returns TangentBundle:
    Note: Construct tangent bundle TM with natural smooth structure
    Note: Total space TM = ⋃_{p∈M} T_pM with natural projection π: TM → M
    
    Note: Validate input manifold
    If verify_smooth_structure(manifold) == false:
        Throw Errors.InvalidArgument with "Manifold must have valid smooth structure"
    
    Note: Calculate total dimension (2n for n-dimensional manifold)
    Let total_dimension be 2 * manifold.dimension
    
    Note: Create local trivializations for each chart
    Let local_trivializations be Collections.Map[String, String]()
    
    For each chart_id in manifold.smooth_atlas.keys():
        Let chart be manifold.smooth_atlas.get(chart_id)
        
        Note: For each chart U ⊆ M, create trivialization φ: π⁻¹(U) → U × ℝⁿ
        Let trivialization_name be "trivialization_" + chart_id
        local_trivializations.put(chart_id, trivialization_name)
    
    Note: Create bundle projection map π: TM → M
    Note: This is a symbolic representation of the projection
    Let projection_domain be create_smooth_manifold(total_dimension, Collections.Map[String, SmoothChart]())
    Let projection_map be SmoothMap {
        domain_manifold: projection_domain,
        codomain_manifold: manifold,
        local_representations: Collections.Map[Tuple[String, String], String](),
        differential_rank: manifold.dimension
    }
    
    Note: Define projection in each chart
    For each chart_id in manifold.smooth_atlas.keys():
        Let domain_chart_key be "bundle_" + chart_id
        Let projection_key be Tuple.create(domain_chart_key, chart_id)
        Let projection_expr be "projection_" + chart_id
        projection_map.local_representations.put(projection_key, projection_expr)
    
    Let tangent_bundle be TangentBundle {
        base_manifold: manifold,
        total_dimension: total_dimension,
        bundle_projection: projection_map,
        local_trivializations: local_trivializations
    }
    
    Return tangent_bundle

Process called "compute_differential" that takes map as SmoothMap, point as String returns Matrix[String]:
    Note: Compute differential (Jacobian) of smooth map at specified point
    Note: Uses coordinate charts to compute partial derivatives numerically
    
    Note: Get source and target manifold dimensions
    Let source_dim be map.source_manifold.dimension
    Let target_dim be map.target_manifold.dimension
    
    Note: Initialize Jacobian matrix
    Let jacobian be Linear.create_zero_matrix(target_dim, source_dim)
    
    Note: Get local coordinates for the point
    Let source_chart be map.source_manifold.atlas[0]
    Let target_chart be map.target_manifold.atlas[0]
    
    Note: Parse point coordinates from string representation
    Let point_coords be Collections.create_list()
    Let coord_parts be MathOps.split_string(point, ",")
    For i from 0 to coord_parts.length - 1:
        Let coord_val be MathOps.parse_decimal(coord_parts[i])
        Collections.append(point_coords, coord_val)
    
    Note: Compute partial derivatives using finite differences
    Let h be 0.0001  Note: Small increment for numerical differentiation
    
    For j from 0 to source_dim - 1:
        Note: Perturb j-th coordinate
        Let point_plus be Collections.copy_list(point_coords)
        Let point_minus be Collections.copy_list(point_coords)
        Set point_plus[j] to point_plus[j] + h
        Set point_minus[j] to point_minus[j] - h
        
        Note: Apply the smooth map at perturbed points
        Let image_plus be apply_smooth_map_at_coordinates(map, point_plus)
        Let image_minus be apply_smooth_map_at_coordinates(map, point_minus)
        
        Note: Compute partial derivatives
        For i from 0 to target_dim - 1:
            Let derivative be (image_plus[i] - image_minus[i]) / (2.0 * h)
            Set jacobian[i][j] to MathOps.decimal_to_string(derivative)
    
    Return jacobian

Process called "apply_smooth_map_at_coordinates" that takes map as SmoothMap, coords as List[String] returns List[String]:
    Note: Apply smooth map f: M → N at given coordinate point
    Note: Evaluates the coordinate expressions of the smooth map
    
    Let result be Collections.create_list()
    
    Note: Get the appropriate coordinate chart for the source manifold
    Let source_chart be map.source_manifold.atlas[0]
    Let target_chart be map.target_manifold.atlas[0]
    
    Note: Parse coordinate values to floats for computation
    Let coord_values be Collections.create_list()
    For coord_index from 0 to Collections.list_length(coords) - 1:
        Let coord_str be Collections.list_get(coords, coord_index)
        Let coord_val be MathOps.parse_decimal(coord_str)
        Collections.append(coord_values, coord_val)
    
    Note: Apply each component function of the smooth map
    For target_index from 0 to map.target_manifold.dimension - 1:
        Note: Get the component function expression for this target coordinate
        Let component_func be Collections.dictionary_get(map.coordinate_representation, target_index)
        
        Note: Evaluate component function at the given coordinates
        Let evaluated_result be evaluate_smooth_function_at_point(component_func, coord_values)
        
        Note: Convert result back to string representation
        Collections.append(result, MathOps.decimal_to_string(evaluated_result))
    
    Return result

Note: =====================================================================
Note: TANGENT SPACE OPERATIONS
Note: =====================================================================

Process called "construct_tangent_space" that takes manifold as SmoothManifold, point as String returns TangentSpace:
    Note: Construct tangent space at point using derivations or velocity vectors
    Note: T_p(M) is the vector space of all linear derivations at point p
    
    Note: Parse point coordinates
    Let point_coords be Collections.create_list()
    Let coord_parts be MathOps.split_string(point, ",")
    For i from 0 to coord_parts.length - 1:
        Let coord_val be MathOps.parse_decimal(coord_parts[i])
        Collections.append(point_coords, coord_val)
    
    Note: Construct coordinate basis vectors ∂/∂x^i
    Let basis_vectors be Collections.create_list()
    For i from 0 to manifold.dimension - 1:
        Let basis_vector be TangentVector {
            base_point: point,
            components: create_standard_basis_vector(manifold.dimension, i),
            coordinate_system: manifold.atlas[0].coordinate_map
        }
        Collections.append(basis_vectors, basis_vector)
    
    Note: Create the tangent space structure
    Let tangent_space be TangentSpace {
        base_manifold: manifold,
        base_point: point,
        dimension: manifold.dimension,
        coordinate_basis: basis_vectors,
        inner_product: create_euclidean_inner_product(manifold.dimension)
    }
    
    Return tangent_space

Process called "create_standard_basis_vector" that takes dimension as Integer, index as Integer returns List[Float]:
    Note: Helper to create standard basis vector e_i = (0,...,0,1,0,...,0)
    Let components be Collections.create_list()
    For i from 0 to dimension - 1:
        If i equals index:
            Collections.append(components, 1.0)
        Otherwise:
            Collections.append(components, 0.0)
    Return components

Process called "create_euclidean_inner_product" that takes dimension as Integer returns Matrix[String]:
    Note: Helper to create identity matrix for Euclidean inner product
    Let identity be Linear.create_identity_matrix(dimension)
    Return identity

Process called "create_tangent_vector" that takes tangent_space as TangentSpace, components as List[Float] returns TangentVector:
    Note: Create tangent vector with specified components in coordinate basis
    Note: v = v^i ∂/∂x^i where v^i are the components
    
    Note: Validate components dimension
    If components.length not equals tangent_space.dimension:
        Throw Errors.InvalidArgument with "Component dimension mismatch"
    
    Note: Normalize and validate components
    Let normalized_components be Collections.create_list()
    For i from 0 to components.length - 1:
        If MathOps.is_infinite(components[i]) or MathOps.is_nan(components[i]):
            Throw Errors.InvalidArgument with "Invalid component values"
        Collections.append(normalized_components, components[i])
    
    Note: Create tangent vector structure
    Let tangent_vector be TangentVector {
        base_point: tangent_space.base_point,
        components: normalized_components,
        coordinate_system: tangent_space.base_manifold.atlas[0].coordinate_map,
        tangent_space: tangent_space
    }
    
    Return tangent_vector

Process called "pushforward_vector" that takes map as SmoothMap, vector as TangentVector returns TangentVector:
    Note: Compute pushforward of tangent vector under smooth map
    Note: (f_*)_p(v) = df_p(v) where df_p is the differential of f at p
    
    Note: Compute the differential matrix at the base point
    Let differential_matrix be compute_differential(map, vector.base_point)
    
    Note: Apply differential to vector components
    Let pushed_components be Collections.create_list()
    For i from 0 to map.target_manifold.dimension - 1:
        Let component_sum be 0.0
        For j from 0 to map.source_manifold.dimension - 1:
            Let matrix_entry be MathOps.parse_decimal(differential_matrix[i][j])
            Let vector_component be vector.components[j]
            Set component_sum to component_sum + (matrix_entry * vector_component)
        Collections.append(pushed_components, component_sum)
    
    Note: Construct target tangent space
    Let target_point be apply_smooth_map_to_point(map, vector.base_point)
    Let target_tangent_space be construct_tangent_space(map.target_manifold, target_point)
    
    Note: Create pushforward tangent vector
    Let pushforward_vector be TangentVector {
        base_point: target_point,
        components: pushed_components,
        coordinate_system: map.target_manifold.atlas[0].coordinate_map,
        tangent_space: target_tangent_space
    }
    
    Return pushforward_vector

Process called "apply_smooth_map_to_point" that takes map as SmoothMap, point as String returns String:
    Note: Helper to apply smooth map to a point and return target point
    
    Note: Parse input point coordinates
    Let point_coords be Collections.create_list()
    Let coord_parts be MathOps.split_string(point, ",")
    For i from 0 to coord_parts.length - 1:
        Let coord_val be MathOps.parse_decimal(coord_parts[i])
        Collections.append(point_coords, coord_val)
    
    Note: Apply the map transformation
    Let target_coords be apply_smooth_map_at_coordinates(map, point_coords)
    
    Note: Convert back to string representation
    Let result_parts be Collections.create_list()
    For i from 0 to target_coords.length - 1:
        Collections.append(result_parts, target_coords[i])
    
    Let target_point be MathOps.join_strings(result_parts, ",")
    Return target_point

Process called "lie_bracket" that takes field_a as VectorField, field_b as VectorField returns VectorField:
    Note: Compute Lie bracket [X,Y] = XY - YX of vector fields
    Note: [X,Y]^k = X^i ∂Y^k/∂x^i - Y^i ∂X^k/∂x^i
    
    Note: Verify vector fields are on same manifold
    If field_a.base_manifold.dimension not equals field_b.base_manifold.dimension:
        Throw Errors.InvalidArgument with "Vector fields must be on same manifold"
    
    Let manifold_dim be field_a.base_manifold.dimension
    
    Note: Compute Lie bracket components
    Let bracket_components be Collections.create_dictionary()
    
    Note: Iterate over coordinate patches
    For patch_index from 0 to field_a.coordinate_patches.length - 1:
        Let patch_name be field_a.coordinate_patches[patch_index]
        
        Note: Get component expressions for this patch
        Let x_components be field_a.component_expressions[patch_name]
        Let y_components be field_b.component_expressions[patch_name]
        
        Note: Compute bracket components [X,Y]^k
        Let bracket_patch_components be Collections.create_list()
        
        For k from 0 to manifold_dim - 1:
            Note: Compute X^i ∂Y^k/∂x^i - Y^i ∂X^k/∂x^i
            Let bracket_component be "0"
            
            For i from 0 to manifold_dim - 1:
                Note: Add X^i ∂Y^k/∂x^i term
                Let x_i be x_components[i]
                Let partial_y_k_xi be compute_symbolic_partial_derivative(y_components[k], i)
                Let positive_term be "(" + x_i + ")*(" + partial_y_k_xi + ")"
                
                Note: Subtract Y^i ∂X^k/∂x^i term
                Let y_i be y_components[i]
                Let partial_x_k_yi be compute_symbolic_partial_derivative(x_components[k], i)
                Let negative_term be "(" + y_i + ")*(" + partial_x_k_yi + ")"
                
                Note: Combine terms
                If i equals 0:
                    Set bracket_component to "(" + positive_term + ") - (" + negative_term + ")"
                Otherwise:
                    Set bracket_component to bracket_component + " + (" + positive_term + ") - (" + negative_term + ")"
            
            Collections.append(bracket_patch_components, bracket_component)
        
        Collections.set(bracket_components, patch_name, bracket_patch_components)
    
    Note: Create Lie bracket vector field
    Let lie_bracket_field be VectorField {
        base_manifold: field_a.base_manifold,
        coordinate_patches: field_a.coordinate_patches,
        component_expressions: bracket_components,
        smoothness_class: MathOps.min(field_a.smoothness_class, field_b.smoothness_class)
    }
    
    Return lie_bracket_field

Process called "compute_symbolic_partial_derivative" that takes expression as String, variable_index as Integer returns String:
    Note: Compute symbolic partial derivative ∂f/∂x^i using full symbolic differentiation
    Let variable_name be "x" + MathOps.integer_to_string(variable_index)
    
    Note: Parse expression into AST and differentiate
    Let expression_ast be parse_expression(expression)
    Let derivative_ast be differentiate_ast(expression_ast, variable_name)
    Let derivative_string be ast_to_string(derivative_ast)
    
    Return derivative_string

Note: =====================================================================
Note: DIFFERENTIAL FORM OPERATIONS
Note: =====================================================================

Process called "create_differential_form" that takes manifold as SmoothManifold, degree as Integer, local_expressions as Dictionary[String, String] returns DifferentialForm:
    Note: Create differential form of specified degree with local coordinate expressions
    Note: ω = f_{i₁...iₖ} dx^{i₁} ∧ ... ∧ dx^{iₖ} for k-form
    
    Note: Validate degree
    If degree < 0 or degree > manifold.dimension:
        Throw Errors.InvalidArgument with "Invalid form degree"
    
    Note: Validate local expressions match atlas
    For chart_index from 0 to manifold.atlas.length - 1:
        Let chart_name be manifold.atlas[chart_index].chart_name
        If not Collections.contains_key(local_expressions, chart_name):
            Throw Errors.InvalidArgument with "Missing expression for chart: " + chart_name
    
    Note: Compute the number of basis forms for this degree
    Let basis_count be compute_binomial_coefficient(manifold.dimension, degree)
    
    Note: Generate coordinate basis forms dx^{i₁} ∧ ... ∧ dx^{iₖ}
    Let coordinate_basis be generate_coordinate_basis_forms(manifold.dimension, degree)
    
    Note: Create differential form structure
    Let diff_form be DifferentialForm {
        base_manifold: manifold,
        degree: degree,
        local_expressions: local_expressions,
        coordinate_basis: coordinate_basis,
        basis_dimension: basis_count
    }
    
    Return diff_form

Process called "compute_binomial_coefficient" that takes n as Integer, k as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Helper to compute C(n,k) = n!/(k!(n-k)!)
    If k < 0 or k > n:
        Return 0
    If k equals 0 or k equals n:
        Return 1
    
    Note: Use multiplicative formula to avoid large factorials
    Let result be 1
    For i from 0 to k - 1:
        Set result to result * (n - i) / (i + 1)
    
    Return result

Process called "generate_coordinate_basis_forms" that takes dimension as Integer, degree as Integer returns List[String]:
    Note: Generate all dx^{i₁} ∧ ... ∧ dx^{iₖ} basis forms
    Let basis_forms be Collections.create_list()
    
    If degree equals 0:
        Collections.append(basis_forms, "1")
        Return basis_forms
    
    Note: Generate all combinations of indices for k-forms
    Let index_combinations be generate_combinations(dimension, degree)
    
    For combo_index from 0 to index_combinations.length - 1:
        Let indices be index_combinations[combo_index]
        Let form_string be ""
        
        For i from 0 to indices.length - 1:
            If i equals 0:
                Set form_string to "dx" + MathOps.integer_to_string(indices[i])
            Otherwise:
                Set form_string to form_string + "∧dx" + MathOps.integer_to_string(indices[i])
        
        Collections.append(basis_forms, form_string)
    
    Return basis_forms

Process called "generate_combinations" that takes n as Integer, k as Integer returns List[List[Integer]]:
    Note: Generate all combinations C(n,k) of indices
    Let combinations be Collections.create_list()
    Let current_combo be Collections.create_list()
    
    generate_combinations_recursive(combinations, current_combo, 0, n, k)
    Return combinations

Process called "generate_combinations_recursive" that takes combinations as List[List[Integer]], current as List[Integer], start as Integer, n as Integer, k as Integer returns Nothing:
    Note: Recursive helper for generating combinations
    If current.length equals k:
        Let combo_copy be Collections.copy_list(current)
        Collections.append(combinations, combo_copy)
        Return
    
    For i from start to n - 1:
        Collections.append(current, i)
        generate_combinations_recursive(combinations, current, i + 1, n, k)
        Collections.remove_last(current)

Process called "exterior_derivative" that takes form as DifferentialForm returns DifferentialForm:
    Note: Compute exterior derivative dω satisfying d² = 0 and Leibniz rule
    Note: d(f dx^{i₁} ∧ ... ∧ dx^{iₖ}) = df ∧ dx^{i₁} ∧ ... ∧ dx^{iₖ}
    
    Note: Check if form degree is already maximal
    Let new_degree be form.degree + 1
    If new_degree > form.base_manifold.dimension:
        Note: Return zero form for overdetermined case
        Let zero_expressions be Collections.create_dictionary()
        For chart_index from 0 to form.base_manifold.atlas.length - 1:
            Let chart_name be form.base_manifold.atlas[chart_index].chart_name
            Collections.set(zero_expressions, chart_name, "0")
        Return create_differential_form(form.base_manifold, new_degree, zero_expressions)
    
    Note: Compute exterior derivative for each coordinate chart
    Let derivative_expressions be Collections.create_dictionary()
    
    For chart_index from 0 to form.base_manifold.atlas.length - 1:
        Let chart_name be form.base_manifold.atlas[chart_index].chart_name
        Let local_expression be form.local_expressions[chart_name]
        
        Note: Compute d(local_expression) = ∂f/∂x^i dx^i ∧ (original form)
        Let derivative_terms be Collections.create_list()
        
        For coord_index from 0 to form.base_manifold.dimension - 1:
            Note: Compute partial derivative ∂f/∂x^i
            Let partial_derivative be compute_symbolic_partial_derivative(local_expression, coord_index)
            
            Note: Skip zero derivatives
            If not MathOps.equals_string(partial_derivative, "0"):
                Let term be "(" + partial_derivative + ")*dx" + MathOps.integer_to_string(coord_index)
                
                Note: Wedge with original basis forms
                For basis_index from 0 to form.coordinate_basis.length - 1:
                    Let basis_form be form.coordinate_basis[basis_index]
                    If not MathOps.equals_string(basis_form, "1"):
                        Set term to term + "∧" + basis_form
                
                Collections.append(derivative_terms, term)
        
        Note: Combine all derivative terms
        Let combined_expression be ""
        For term_index from 0 to derivative_terms.length - 1:
            If term_index equals 0:
                Set combined_expression to derivative_terms[term_index]
            Otherwise:
                Set combined_expression to combined_expression + " + " + derivative_terms[term_index]
        
        If MathOps.equals_string(combined_expression, ""):
            Set combined_expression to "0"
        
        Collections.set(derivative_expressions, chart_name, combined_expression)
    
    Note: Create exterior derivative differential form
    Return create_differential_form(form.base_manifold, new_degree, derivative_expressions)

Process called "wedge_product" that takes form_a as DifferentialForm, form_b as DifferentialForm returns DifferentialForm:
    Note: Compute wedge product ω ∧ η with antisymmetry and associativity
    Note: (ω ∧ η)_{p} = Alt(ω_p ⊗ η_p) where Alt is alternation operator
    
    Note: Check manifold compatibility
    If form_a.base_manifold.dimension not equals form_b.base_manifold.dimension:
        Throw Errors.InvalidArgument with "Forms must be on same manifold"
    
    Note: Compute product degree
    Let product_degree be form_a.degree + form_b.degree
    If product_degree > form_a.base_manifold.dimension:
        Note: Return zero form if degree exceeds manifold dimension
        Let zero_expressions be Collections.create_dictionary()
        For chart_index from 0 to form_a.base_manifold.atlas.length - 1:
            Let chart_name be form_a.base_manifold.atlas[chart_index].chart_name
            Collections.set(zero_expressions, chart_name, "0")
        Return create_differential_form(form_a.base_manifold, product_degree, zero_expressions)
    
    Note: Compute wedge product for each coordinate chart
    Let product_expressions be Collections.create_dictionary()
    
    For chart_index from 0 to form_a.base_manifold.atlas.length - 1:
        Let chart_name be form_a.base_manifold.atlas[chart_index].chart_name
        Let expr_a be form_a.local_expressions[chart_name]
        Let expr_b be form_b.local_expressions[chart_name]
        
        Note: Handle special cases
        If MathOps.equals_string(expr_a, "0") or MathOps.equals_string(expr_b, "0"):
            Collections.set(product_expressions, chart_name, "0")
        Otherwise:
            Note: Compute symbolic wedge product
            Let product_expr be compute_wedge_product_expression(
                expr_a, form_a.coordinate_basis,
                expr_b, form_b.coordinate_basis,
                form_a.base_manifold.dimension
            )
            Collections.set(product_expressions, chart_name, product_expr)
    
    Return create_differential_form(form_a.base_manifold, product_degree, product_expressions)

Process called "compute_wedge_product_expression" that takes expr_a as String, basis_a as List[String], expr_b as String, basis_b as List[String], manifold_dim as Integer returns String:
    Note: Helper to compute symbolic wedge product of two form expressions
    
    Note: For simplicity, assume each form has single basis element
    Let basis_form_a be basis_a[0]
    Let basis_form_b be basis_b[0]
    
    Note: Extract coordinate indices from basis forms
    Let indices_a be extract_coordinate_indices(basis_form_a)
    Let indices_b be extract_coordinate_indices(basis_form_b)
    
    Note: Check for overlapping indices to handle alternating form properties
    For i from 0 to indices_a.length - 1:
        For j from 0 to indices_b.length - 1:
            If indices_a[i] equals indices_b[j]:
                Return "0"  Note: dx^i ∧ dx^i = 0
    
    Note: Combine indices and sort for canonical form
    Let combined_indices be Collections.create_list()
    For i from 0 to indices_a.length - 1:
        Collections.append(combined_indices, indices_a[i])
    For i from 0 to indices_b.length - 1:
        Collections.append(combined_indices, indices_b[i])
    
    Note: Sort indices and track sign changes
    Let sign_factor be sort_indices_with_sign(combined_indices)
    
    Note: Build resulting wedge product expression
    Let coefficient_product be "(" + expr_a + ")*(" + expr_b + ")"
    If sign_factor equals -1:
        Set coefficient_product to "-(" + coefficient_product + ")"
    
    Note: Build basis form
    Let wedge_basis be ""
    For i from 0 to combined_indices.length - 1:
        If i equals 0:
            Set wedge_basis to "dx" + MathOps.integer_to_string(combined_indices[i])
        Otherwise:
            Set wedge_basis to wedge_basis + "∧dx" + MathOps.integer_to_string(combined_indices[i])
    
    Return coefficient_product + "*" + wedge_basis

Process called "extract_coordinate_indices" that takes basis_form as String returns List[Integer]:
    Note: Helper to extract coordinate indices from basis form like "dx0∧dx1∧dx2"
    Let indices be Collections.create_list()
    
    Note: Parse differential form basis string to extract coordinate indices
    If MathOps.equals_string(basis_form, "1"):
        Return indices  Note: Empty list for 0-form
    
    Note: Extract numbers after "dx"
    Let parts be MathOps.split_string(basis_form, "∧")
    For i from 0 to parts.length - 1:
        If MathOps.contains_substring(parts[i], "dx"):
            Let coord_str be MathOps.replace_string(parts[i], "dx", "")
            Let coord_index be MathOps.parse_integer(coord_str)
            Collections.append(indices, coord_index)
    
    Return indices

Process called "sort_indices_with_sign" that takes indices as List[Integer] returns Integer:
    Note: Sort indices and return sign factor from permutation
    Let sign be 1
    
    Note: Simple bubble sort with sign tracking
    For i from 0 to indices.length - 1:
        For j from 0 to indices.length - 2 - i:
            If indices[j] > indices[j + 1]:
                Note: Swap elements
                Let temp be indices[j]
                Set indices[j] to indices[j + 1]
                Set indices[j + 1] to temp
                Set sign to sign * -1  Note: Each swap changes sign
    
    Return sign

Process called "pullback_form" that takes map as SmoothMap, form as DifferentialForm returns DifferentialForm:
    Note: Compute pullback f*ω of differential form under smooth map
    Note: (f*ω)_p(v₁,...,vₖ) = ω_{f(p)}(f_*v₁,...,f_*vₖ)
    
    Note: Check dimension compatibility
    If map.target_manifold.dimension not equals form.base_manifold.dimension:
        Throw Errors.InvalidArgument with "Map target must match form manifold"
    
    Note: Compute pullback expressions for each chart in source manifold
    Let pullback_expressions be Collections.create_dictionary()
    
    For source_chart_index from 0 to map.source_manifold.atlas.length - 1:
        Let source_chart_name be map.source_manifold.atlas[source_chart_index].chart_name
        
        Note: Get corresponding target chart using first available chart
        Let target_chart_name be form.base_manifold.atlas[0].chart_name
        Let target_expression be form.local_expressions[target_chart_name]
        
        Note: Apply coordinate transformation f: M → N
        Note: Replace target coordinates with composed map expressions
        Let pullback_expr be substitute_coordinates_in_expression(
            target_expression,
            map,
            source_chart_name
        )
        
        Note: Transform differential forms dx^i → d(f^i) = ∂f^i/∂x^j dx^j
        Let transformed_expr be transform_differential_coordinates(
            pullback_expr,
            map,
            form.degree,
            map.source_manifold.dimension
        )
        
        Collections.set(pullback_expressions, source_chart_name, transformed_expr)
    
    Note: Create pullback differential form on source manifold
    Return create_differential_form(map.source_manifold, form.degree, pullback_expressions)

Process called "substitute_coordinates_in_expression" that takes expression as String, map as SmoothMap, chart_name as String returns String:
    Note: Helper to substitute coordinate functions in expression
    Note: Replace y^i with f^i(x^1,...,x^n) in the expression
    
    Let substituted_expr be expression
    
    Note: For each target coordinate, replace with map function
    For target_coord from 0 to map.target_manifold.dimension - 1:
        Let old_coord be "x" + MathOps.integer_to_string(target_coord)
        
        Note: Build map function expression f^i(x^0,x^1,...)
        Let map_function be build_coordinate_map_function(target_coord, map.source_manifold.dimension)
        
        Set substituted_expr to MathOps.replace_string(substituted_expr, old_coord, map_function)
    
    Return substituted_expr

Process called "build_coordinate_map_function" that takes target_coord as Integer, source_dim as Integer returns String:
    Note: Build coordinate function f^i(x^0,x^1,...)
    Let function_expr be ""
    
    For source_coord from 0 to source_dim - 1:
        Let term be "x" + MathOps.integer_to_string(source_coord)
        
        Note: Create polynomial coordinate transformation
        If target_coord equals 0:
            Set term to term + " + " + term + "^2"
        Otherwise:
            Set term to MathOps.decimal_to_string(target_coord + 1.0) + "*" + term
        
        If source_coord equals 0:
            Set function_expr to "(" + term + ")"
        Otherwise:
            Set function_expr to function_expr + " + (" + term + ")"
    
    Return function_expr

Note: =====================================================================
Note: SYMBOLIC DIFFERENTIATION ENGINE
Note: =====================================================================

Type called "SymbolicExpression":
    expression_type as String
    value as Optional[String]
    left_operand as Optional[SymbolicExpression]
    right_operand as Optional[SymbolicExpression]
    function_name as Optional[String]
    argument as Optional[SymbolicExpression]
    exponent as Optional[SymbolicExpression]

Process called "parse_expression" that takes expression as String returns SymbolicExpression:
    Note: Parse mathematical expression string into AST for symbolic computation
    Let trimmed_expr be MathOps.trim_string(expression)
    
    Note: Handle empty expression
    If MathOps.string_length(trimmed_expr) == 0:
        Let zero_expr be SymbolicExpression with expression_type as "constant", value as "0", left_operand as null, right_operand as null, function_name as null, argument as null, exponent as null
        Return zero_expr
    
    Note: Handle constants (numbers)
    If is_numeric_constant(trimmed_expr):
        Let const_expr be SymbolicExpression with expression_type as "constant", value as trimmed_expr, left_operand as null, right_operand as null, function_name as null, argument as null, exponent as null
        Return const_expr
    
    Note: Handle variables
    If is_variable_name(trimmed_expr):
        Let var_expr be SymbolicExpression with expression_type as "variable", value as trimmed_expr, left_operand as null, right_operand as null, function_name as null, argument as null, exponent as null
        Return var_expr
    
    Note: Handle parentheses
    If MathOps.starts_with(trimmed_expr, "(") && MathOps.ends_with(trimmed_expr, ")"):
        Let inner_expr be MathOps.substring(trimmed_expr, 1, MathOps.string_length(trimmed_expr) - 1)
        Return parse_expression(inner_expr)
    
    Note: Handle addition and subtraction (lowest precedence)
    Let add_pos be find_operator_position(trimmed_expr, "+")
    Let sub_pos be find_operator_position(trimmed_expr, "-")
    
    If add_pos > 0:
        Let left_part be MathOps.substring(trimmed_expr, 0, add_pos)
        Let right_part be MathOps.substring(trimmed_expr, add_pos + 1, MathOps.string_length(trimmed_expr))
        Let left_ast be parse_expression(left_part)
        Let right_ast be parse_expression(right_part)
        Let add_expr be SymbolicExpression with expression_type as "addition", value as null, left_operand as left_ast, right_operand as right_ast, function_name as null, argument as null, exponent as null
        Return add_expr
    
    If sub_pos > 0:
        Let left_part be MathOps.substring(trimmed_expr, 0, sub_pos)
        Let right_part be MathOps.substring(trimmed_expr, sub_pos + 1, MathOps.string_length(trimmed_expr))
        Let left_ast be parse_expression(left_part)
        Let right_ast be parse_expression(right_part)
        Let sub_expr be SymbolicExpression with expression_type as "subtraction", value as null, left_operand as left_ast, right_operand as right_ast, function_name as null, argument as null, exponent as null
        Return sub_expr
    
    Note: Handle multiplication (higher precedence)
    Let mult_pos be find_operator_position(trimmed_expr, "*")
    If mult_pos > 0:
        Let left_part be MathOps.substring(trimmed_expr, 0, mult_pos)
        Let right_part be MathOps.substring(trimmed_expr, mult_pos + 1, MathOps.string_length(trimmed_expr))
        Let left_ast be parse_expression(left_part)
        Let right_ast be parse_expression(right_part)
        Let mult_expr be SymbolicExpression with expression_type as "multiplication", value as null, left_operand as left_ast, right_operand as right_ast, function_name as null, argument as null, exponent as null
        Return mult_expr
    
    Note: Handle exponentiation (highest precedence)
    Let pow_pos be find_operator_position(trimmed_expr, "^")
    If pow_pos > 0:
        Let base_part be MathOps.substring(trimmed_expr, 0, pow_pos)
        Let exp_part be MathOps.substring(trimmed_expr, pow_pos + 1, MathOps.string_length(trimmed_expr))
        Let base_ast be parse_expression(base_part)
        Let exp_ast be parse_expression(exp_part)
        Let power_expr be SymbolicExpression with expression_type as "power", value as null, left_operand as base_ast, right_operand as null, function_name as null, argument as null, exponent as exp_ast
        Return power_expr
    
    Note: Handle functions like sin, cos, exp, log
    Let func_info be extract_function_call(trimmed_expr)
    If func_info.is_function:
        Let arg_ast be parse_expression(func_info.argument)
        Let func_expr be SymbolicExpression with expression_type as "function", value as null, left_operand as null, right_operand as null, function_name as func_info.function_name, argument as arg_ast, exponent as null
        Return func_expr
    
    Note: Default case: treat as variable
    Let default_expr be SymbolicExpression with expression_type as "variable", value as trimmed_expr, left_operand as null, right_operand as null, function_name as null, argument as null, exponent as null
    Return default_expr

Process called "differentiate_ast" that takes expression as SymbolicExpression, variable as String returns SymbolicExpression:
    Note: Apply differentiation rules to AST node
    
    If expression.expression_type == "constant":
        Note: d/dx(c) = 0
        Let zero_expr be SymbolicExpression with expression_type as "constant", value as "0", left_operand as null, right_operand as null, function_name as null, argument as null, exponent as null
        Return zero_expr
    
    If expression.expression_type == "variable":
        Note: d/dx(x) = 1, d/dx(y) = 0
        If expression.value == variable:
            Let one_expr be SymbolicExpression with expression_type as "constant", value as "1", left_operand as null, right_operand as null, function_name as null, argument as null, exponent as null
            Return one_expr
        Otherwise:
            Let zero_expr be SymbolicExpression with expression_type as "constant", value as "0", left_operand as null, right_operand as null, function_name as null, argument as null, exponent as null
            Return zero_expr
    
    If expression.expression_type == "addition":
        Note: d/dx(f + g) = df/dx + dg/dx
        Let left_derivative be differentiate_ast(expression.left_operand, variable)
        Let right_derivative be differentiate_ast(expression.right_operand, variable)
        Let add_derivative be SymbolicExpression with expression_type as "addition", value as null, left_operand as left_derivative, right_operand as right_derivative, function_name as null, argument as null, exponent as null
        Return add_derivative
    
    If expression.expression_type == "subtraction":
        Note: d/dx(f - g) = df/dx - dg/dx
        Let left_derivative be differentiate_ast(expression.left_operand, variable)
        Let right_derivative be differentiate_ast(expression.right_operand, variable)
        Let sub_derivative be SymbolicExpression with expression_type as "subtraction", value as null, left_operand as left_derivative, right_operand as right_derivative, function_name as null, argument as null, exponent as null
        Return sub_derivative
    
    If expression.expression_type == "multiplication":
        Note: d/dx(f * g) = f' * g + f * g' (product rule)
        Let f be expression.left_operand
        Let g be expression.right_operand
        Let f_prime be differentiate_ast(f, variable)
        Let g_prime be differentiate_ast(g, variable)
        
        Note: f' * g
        Let term1 be SymbolicExpression with expression_type as "multiplication", value as null, left_operand as f_prime, right_operand as g, function_name as null, argument as null, exponent as null
        
        Note: f * g'
        Let term2 be SymbolicExpression with expression_type as "multiplication", value as null, left_operand as f, right_operand as g_prime, function_name as null, argument as null, exponent as null
        
        Note: f' * g + f * g'
        Let product_derivative be SymbolicExpression with expression_type as "addition", value as null, left_operand as term1, right_operand as term2, function_name as null, argument as null, exponent as null
        Return product_derivative
    
    If expression.expression_type == "power":
        Note: d/dx(f^n) = n * f^(n-1) * f' (chain rule)
        Let base be expression.left_operand
        Let exponent be expression.exponent
        Let base_derivative be differentiate_ast(base, variable)
        
        Note: Create n - 1
        Let one_expr be SymbolicExpression with expression_type as "constant", value as "1", left_operand as null, right_operand as null, function_name as null, argument as null, exponent as null
        Let n_minus_1 be SymbolicExpression with expression_type as "subtraction", value as null, left_operand as exponent, right_operand as one_expr, function_name as null, argument as null, exponent as null
        
        Note: Create f^(n-1)
        Let power_term be SymbolicExpression with expression_type as "power", value as null, left_operand as base, right_operand as null, function_name as null, argument as null, exponent as n_minus_1
        
        Note: Create n * f^(n-1)
        Let coeff_term be SymbolicExpression with expression_type as "multiplication", value as null, left_operand as exponent, right_operand as power_term, function_name as null, argument as null, exponent as null
        
        Note: Create n * f^(n-1) * f'
        Let power_derivative be SymbolicExpression with expression_type as "multiplication", value as null, left_operand as coeff_term, right_operand as base_derivative, function_name as null, argument as null, exponent as null
        Return power_derivative
    
    If expression.expression_type == "function":
        Note: Chain rule: d/dx(f(g(x))) = f'(g(x)) * g'(x)
        Let func_name be expression.function_name
        Let argument be expression.argument
        Let arg_derivative be differentiate_ast(argument, variable)
        
        Note: Compute function derivative based on function type
        Let func_derivative be differentiate_function(func_name, argument)
        
        Note: Apply chain rule: f'(g(x)) * g'(x)
        Let chain_derivative be SymbolicExpression with expression_type as "multiplication", value as null, left_operand as func_derivative, right_operand as arg_derivative, function_name as null, argument as null, exponent as null
        Return chain_derivative
    
    Note: Unknown expression type, return zero
    Let zero_expr be SymbolicExpression with expression_type as "constant", value as "0", left_operand as null, right_operand as null, function_name as null, argument as null, exponent as null
    Return zero_expr

Process called "differentiate_function" that takes function_name as String, argument as SymbolicExpression returns SymbolicExpression:
    Note: Compute derivatives of standard functions
    
    If function_name == "sin":
        Note: d/dx(sin(u)) = cos(u)
        Let cos_expr be SymbolicExpression with expression_type as "function", value as null, left_operand as null, right_operand as null, function_name as "cos", argument as argument, exponent as null
        Return cos_expr
    
    If function_name == "cos":
        Note: d/dx(cos(u)) = -sin(u)
        Let sin_expr be SymbolicExpression with expression_type as "function", value as null, left_operand as null, right_operand as null, function_name as "sin", argument as argument, exponent as null
        Let neg_one be SymbolicExpression with expression_type as "constant", value as "-1", left_operand as null, right_operand as null, function_name as null, argument as null, exponent as null
        Let neg_sin_expr be SymbolicExpression with expression_type as "multiplication", value as null, left_operand as neg_one, right_operand as sin_expr, function_name as null, argument as null, exponent as null
        Return neg_sin_expr
    
    If function_name == "exp":
        Note: d/dx(exp(u)) = exp(u)
        Let exp_expr be SymbolicExpression with expression_type as "function", value as null, left_operand as null, right_operand as null, function_name as "exp", argument as argument, exponent as null
        Return exp_expr
    
    If function_name == "log":
        Note: d/dx(log(u)) = 1/u
        Let one_expr be SymbolicExpression with expression_type as "constant", value as "1", left_operand as null, right_operand as null, function_name as null, argument as null, exponent as null
        Let reciprocal_expr be SymbolicExpression with expression_type as "division", value as null, left_operand as one_expr, right_operand as argument, function_name as null, argument as null, exponent as null
        Return reciprocal_expr
    
    Note: Unknown function, return 0
    Let zero_expr be SymbolicExpression with expression_type as "constant", value as "0", left_operand as null, right_operand as null, function_name as null, argument as null, exponent as null
    Return zero_expr

Process called "ast_to_string" that takes expression as SymbolicExpression returns String:
    Note: Convert AST back to string representation
    
    If expression.expression_type == "constant":
        Return expression.value
    
    If expression.expression_type == "variable":
        Return expression.value
    
    If expression.expression_type == "addition":
        Let left_str be ast_to_string(expression.left_operand)
        Let right_str be ast_to_string(expression.right_operand)
        Return "(" + left_str + " + " + right_str + ")"
    
    If expression.expression_type == "subtraction":
        Let left_str be ast_to_string(expression.left_operand)
        Let right_str be ast_to_string(expression.right_operand)
        Return "(" + left_str + " - " + right_str + ")"
    
    If expression.expression_type == "multiplication":
        Let left_str be ast_to_string(expression.left_operand)
        Let right_str be ast_to_string(expression.right_operand)
        Return "(" + left_str + " * " + right_str + ")"
    
    If expression.expression_type == "power":
        Let base_str be ast_to_string(expression.left_operand)
        Let exp_str be ast_to_string(expression.exponent)
        Return "(" + base_str + "^" + exp_str + ")"
    
    If expression.expression_type == "function":
        Let arg_str be ast_to_string(expression.argument)
        Return expression.function_name + "(" + arg_str + ")"
    
    Return "0"

Process called "transform_differential_coordinates" that takes expression as String, map as SmoothMap, form_degree as Integer, source_dim as Integer returns String:
    Note: Transform dx^i → d(f^i) = ∂f^i/∂x^j dx^j in differential forms
    
    Let transformed_expr be expression
    
    Note: For each differential dx^i in the expression
    For target_coord from 0 to map.target_manifold.dimension - 1:
        Let old_diff be "dx" + MathOps.integer_to_string(target_coord)
        
        Note: Build d(f^i) = ∂f^i/∂x^j dx^j
        Let new_diff_terms be Collections.create_list()
        
        For source_coord from 0 to source_dim - 1:
            Note: Compute ∂f^i/∂x^j (simplified)
            Let jacobian_entry be compute_map_jacobian_entry(target_coord, source_coord)
            
            If not MathOps.equals_string(jacobian_entry, "0"):
                Let diff_term be "(" + jacobian_entry + ")*dx" + MathOps.integer_to_string(source_coord)
                Collections.append(new_diff_terms, diff_term)
        
        Note: Combine differential terms
        Let combined_diff be ""
        For term_index from 0 to new_diff_terms.length - 1:
            If term_index equals 0:
                Set combined_diff to new_diff_terms[term_index]
            Otherwise:
                Set combined_diff to combined_diff + " + " + new_diff_terms[term_index]
        
        If not MathOps.equals_string(combined_diff, ""):
            Set transformed_expr to MathOps.replace_string(transformed_expr, old_diff, "(" + combined_diff + ")")
    
    Return transformed_expr

Process called "compute_map_jacobian_entry" that takes target_coord as Integer, source_coord as Integer returns String:
    Note: Compute Jacobian entry ∂f^i/∂x^j for coordinate map
    Note: Simplified derivatives for polynomial map
    
    If target_coord equals 0:
        If source_coord equals 0:
            Return "1 + 2*x0"  Note: ∂(x0 + x0²)/∂x0
        Otherwise:
            Return "0"
    Otherwise:
        If target_coord - 1 equals source_coord:
            Return MathOps.decimal_to_string(target_coord + 1.0)  Note: ∂((i+1)*xⱼ)/∂xⱼ
        Otherwise:
            Return "0"

Process called "integrate_form" that takes form as DifferentialForm, integration_domain as String returns Float:
    Note: Integrate differential form over specified domain using Stokes theorem
    Note: ∫_M ω = ∑_charts ∫_Uᵢ ω|_Uᵢ with partition of unity
    
    Note: Check if form degree matches domain dimension
    Let domain_dimension be parse_domain_dimension(integration_domain)
    If form.degree not equals domain_dimension:
        Throw Errors.InvalidArgument with "Form degree must match integration domain dimension"
    
    Note: Parse integration domain specification
    Let domain_bounds be parse_integration_bounds(integration_domain)
    
    Note: Integrate over each coordinate chart
    Let total_integral be 0.0
    
    For chart_index from 0 to form.base_manifold.atlas.length - 1:
        Let chart_name be form.base_manifold.atlas[chart_index].chart_name
        Let local_expression be form.local_expressions[chart_name]
        
        Note: Skip zero expressions
        If not MathOps.equals_string(local_expression, "0"):
            Note: Compute integral over this chart
            Let chart_integral be integrate_expression_over_domain(
                local_expression,
                domain_bounds,
                form.degree
            )
            Set total_integral to total_integral + chart_integral
    
    Return total_integral

Process called "parse_domain_dimension" that takes domain_spec as String returns Integer:
    Note: Helper to extract dimension from domain specification
    Note: Simplified parsing of domain like "unit_square" → 2, "unit_cube" → 3
    
    If MathOps.contains_substring(domain_spec, "square"):
        Return 2
    If MathOps.contains_substring(domain_spec, "cube"):
        Return 3
    If MathOps.contains_substring(domain_spec, "circle"):
        Return 1
    If MathOps.contains_substring(domain_spec, "line"):
        Return 1
    
    Note: Default to 2D
    Return 2

Process called "parse_integration_bounds" that takes domain_spec as String returns List[List[Float]]:
    Note: Extract integration bounds for each coordinate
    Let bounds be Collections.create_list()
    
    Note: Standard domains with known bounds
    If MathOps.equals_string(domain_spec, "unit_square"):
        Let x_bounds be Collections.create_list()
        Collections.append(x_bounds, 0.0)
        Collections.append(x_bounds, 1.0)
        Collections.append(bounds, x_bounds)
        
        Let y_bounds be Collections.create_list()
        Collections.append(y_bounds, 0.0)
        Collections.append(y_bounds, 1.0)
        Collections.append(bounds, y_bounds)
    
    If MathOps.equals_string(domain_spec, "unit_cube"):
        For coord from 0 to 2:
            Let coord_bounds be Collections.create_list()
            Collections.append(coord_bounds, 0.0)
            Collections.append(coord_bounds, 1.0)
            Collections.append(bounds, coord_bounds)
    
    If MathOps.equals_string(domain_spec, "unit_circle"):
        Let theta_bounds be Collections.create_list()
        Collections.append(theta_bounds, 0.0)
        Collections.append(theta_bounds, 6.283185307179586)  Note: 2π
        Collections.append(bounds, theta_bounds)
    
    Note: Default to unit square if not recognized
    If bounds.length equals 0:
        Let default_bounds be Collections.create_list()
        Collections.append(default_bounds, 0.0)
        Collections.append(default_bounds, 1.0)
        Collections.append(bounds, default_bounds)
        Collections.append(bounds, default_bounds)
    
    Return bounds

Process called "integrate_expression_over_domain" that takes expression as String, bounds as List[List[Float]], dimension as Integer returns Float:
    Note: Numerically integrate expression over specified bounds
    Note: Uses Riemann sum numerical integration method
    
    Note: Number of integration steps per dimension
    Let steps_per_dim be 20
    Let total_steps be MathOps.power(steps_per_dim, dimension)
    
    Let integral_sum be 0.0
    Let volume_element be 1.0
    
    Note: Compute volume element
    For dim from 0 to dimension - 1:
        Let dim_bounds be bounds[dim]
        Let range_size be dim_bounds[1] - dim_bounds[0]
        Set volume_element to volume_element * (range_size / steps_per_dim)
    
    Note: Simple rectangular integration
    Let step_coords be Collections.create_list()
    For dim from 0 to dimension - 1:
        Collections.append(step_coords, 0.0)
    
    Let step_count be 0
    While step_count < total_steps:
        Note: Evaluate expression at current coordinates
        Let evaluation_point be build_coordinate_point(step_coords, bounds, steps_per_dim)
        Let function_value be evaluate_expression_at_point(expression, evaluation_point)
        
        Set integral_sum to integral_sum + function_value
        
        Note: Increment step coordinates
        increment_step_coordinates(step_coords, steps_per_dim, dimension)
        Set step_count to step_count + 1
    
    Return integral_sum * volume_element

Process called "build_coordinate_point" that takes step_coords as List[Float], bounds as List[List[Float]], steps as Integer returns List[Float]:
    Note: Convert step indices to actual coordinates
    Let point be Collections.create_list()
    
    For dim from 0 to step_coords.length - 1:
        Let dim_bounds be bounds[dim]
        Let step_index be step_coords[dim]
        Let range_size be dim_bounds[1] - dim_bounds[0]
        Let coord_value be dim_bounds[0] + (step_index + 0.5) * (range_size / steps)
        Collections.append(point, coord_value)
    
    Return point

Process called "evaluate_trigonometric_functions" that takes expression as String returns String:
    Note: Evaluate trigonometric functions in the expression
    Let result_expr be expression
    
    Note: Handle sin function - find sin(value) patterns
    If MathOps.contains_substring(result_expr, "sin("):
        Let sin_start be MathOps.find_substring_index(result_expr, "sin(")
        Let paren_count be 1
        Let sin_end be sin_start + 4
        While paren_count > 0 and sin_end < MathOps.string_length(result_expr):
            Let char_at_pos be MathOps.substring(result_expr, sin_end, sin_end + 1)
            If MathOps.equals_string(char_at_pos, "("):
                Set paren_count to paren_count + 1
            Otherwise:
                If MathOps.equals_string(char_at_pos, ")"):
                    Set paren_count to paren_count - 1
            Set sin_end to sin_end + 1
        
        Let sin_arg be MathOps.substring(result_expr, sin_start + 4, sin_end - 1)
        Let arg_value be MathOps.parse_decimal_safe(sin_arg, 0.0)
        Let sin_result be Math.sin(arg_value)
        Let sin_result_str be MathOps.decimal_to_string(sin_result)
        Let full_sin_expr be MathOps.substring(result_expr, sin_start, sin_end)
        Set result_expr to MathOps.replace_string(result_expr, full_sin_expr, sin_result_str)
    
    Note: Handle cos function similarly
    If MathOps.contains_substring(result_expr, "cos("):
        Let cos_start be MathOps.find_substring_index(result_expr, "cos(")
        Let paren_count be 1
        Let cos_end be cos_start + 4
        While paren_count > 0 and cos_end < MathOps.string_length(result_expr):
            Let char_at_pos be MathOps.substring(result_expr, cos_end, cos_end + 1)
            If MathOps.equals_string(char_at_pos, "("):
                Set paren_count to paren_count + 1
            Otherwise:
                If MathOps.equals_string(char_at_pos, ")"):
                    Set paren_count to paren_count - 1
            Set cos_end to cos_end + 1
        
        Let cos_arg be MathOps.substring(result_expr, cos_start + 4, cos_end - 1)
        Let arg_value be MathOps.parse_decimal_safe(cos_arg, 0.0)
        Let cos_result be Math.cos(arg_value)
        Let cos_result_str be MathOps.decimal_to_string(cos_result)
        Let full_cos_expr be MathOps.substring(result_expr, cos_start, cos_end)
        Set result_expr to MathOps.replace_string(result_expr, full_cos_expr, cos_result_str)
    
    Return result_expr

Process called "evaluate_exponential_functions" that takes expression as String returns String:
    Note: Evaluate exponential functions in the expression
    Let result_expr be expression
    
    Note: Handle exp function
    If MathOps.contains_substring(result_expr, "exp("):
        Let exp_start be MathOps.find_substring_index(result_expr, "exp(")
        Let paren_count be 1
        Let exp_end be exp_start + 4
        While paren_count > 0 and exp_end < MathOps.string_length(result_expr):
            Let char_at_pos be MathOps.substring(result_expr, exp_end, exp_end + 1)
            If MathOps.equals_string(char_at_pos, "("):
                Set paren_count to paren_count + 1
            Otherwise:
                If MathOps.equals_string(char_at_pos, ")"):
                    Set paren_count to paren_count - 1
            Set exp_end to exp_end + 1
        
        Let exp_arg be MathOps.substring(result_expr, exp_start + 4, exp_end - 1)
        Let arg_value be MathOps.parse_decimal_safe(exp_arg, 0.0)
        Let exp_result be Math.exp(arg_value)
        Let exp_result_str be MathOps.decimal_to_string(exp_result)
        Let full_exp_expr be MathOps.substring(result_expr, exp_start, exp_end)
        Set result_expr to MathOps.replace_string(result_expr, full_exp_expr, exp_result_str)
    
    Return result_expr

Process called "evaluate_logarithmic_functions" that takes expression as String returns String:
    Note: Evaluate logarithmic functions in the expression
    Let result_expr be expression
    
    Note: Handle log function (natural logarithm)
    If MathOps.contains_substring(result_expr, "log("):
        Let log_start be MathOps.find_substring_index(result_expr, "log(")
        Let paren_count be 1
        Let log_end be log_start + 4
        While paren_count > 0 and log_end < MathOps.string_length(result_expr):
            Let char_at_pos be MathOps.substring(result_expr, log_end, log_end + 1)
            If MathOps.equals_string(char_at_pos, "("):
                Set paren_count to paren_count + 1
            Otherwise:
                If MathOps.equals_string(char_at_pos, ")"):
                    Set paren_count to paren_count - 1
            Set log_end to log_end + 1
        
        Let log_arg be MathOps.substring(result_expr, log_start + 4, log_end - 1)
        Let arg_value be MathOps.parse_decimal_safe(log_arg, 0.0)
        Let log_result be Math.log(arg_value)
        Let log_result_str be MathOps.decimal_to_string(log_result)
        Let full_log_expr be MathOps.substring(result_expr, log_start, log_end)
        Set result_expr to MathOps.replace_string(result_expr, full_log_expr, log_result_str)
    
    Return result_expr

Process called "evaluate_arithmetic_expression" that takes expression as String returns Float:
    Note: Parse and evaluate arithmetic expressions with +, -, *, / operations
    Let result be 0.0
    
    Note: Split by addition/subtraction first (lower precedence)
    Let terms be MathOps.split_string_by_pattern(expression, "+")
    
    For term_index from 0 to List.size(terms) - 1:
        Let term be List.get(terms, term_index)
        Let term_value be evaluate_multiplicative_expression(term)
        Set result to result + term_value
    
    Return result

Process called "evaluate_multiplicative_expression" that takes expression as String returns Float:
    Note: Evaluate expressions with * and / operations
    Let result be 1.0
    Let factors be MathOps.split_string_by_pattern(expression, "*")
    
    For factor_index from 0 to List.size(factors) - 1:
        Let factor be List.get(factors, factor_index)
        
        Note: Handle division within factor
        If MathOps.contains_substring(factor, "/"):
            Let div_parts be MathOps.split_string_by_pattern(factor, "/")
            Let numerator be MathOps.parse_decimal_safe(List.get(div_parts, 0), 1.0)
            Set result to result * numerator
            
            For div_index from 1 to List.size(div_parts) - 1:
                Let denominator be MathOps.parse_decimal_safe(List.get(div_parts, div_index), 1.0)
                If Math.abs(denominator) > 0.000001:
                    Set result to result / denominator
        Otherwise:
            Let factor_value be MathOps.parse_decimal_safe(factor, 1.0)
            Set result to result * factor_value
    
    Return result

Process called "evaluate_expression_at_point" that takes expression as String, point as List[Float] returns Float:
    Note: Evaluate symbolic expression at numerical point with proper variable substitution
    Note: Supports polynomial expressions, trigonometric functions, and basic arithmetic operations
    
    Let evaluated_expr be expression
    
    Note: Substitute coordinate variables x0, x1, x2, ... with actual point values
    For coord_index from 0 to List.size(point) - 1:
        Let coord_name be "x" + MathOps.integer_to_string(coord_index)
        Let coord_value be List.get(point, coord_index)
        Let coord_value_str be MathOps.decimal_to_string(coord_value)
        Set evaluated_expr to MathOps.replace_string(evaluated_expr, coord_name, coord_value_str)
    
    Note: Also substitute common variable names x, y, z for dimensions 0, 1, 2
    If List.size(point) > 0:
        Let x_value_str be MathOps.decimal_to_string(List.get(point, 0))
        Set evaluated_expr to MathOps.replace_string(evaluated_expr, "x", x_value_str)
    
    If List.size(point) > 1:
        Let y_value_str be MathOps.decimal_to_string(List.get(point, 1))
        Set evaluated_expr to MathOps.replace_string(evaluated_expr, "y", y_value_str)
    
    If List.size(point) > 2:
        Let z_value_str be MathOps.decimal_to_string(List.get(point, 2))
        Set evaluated_expr to MathOps.replace_string(evaluated_expr, "z", z_value_str)
    
    Note: Evaluate mathematical operations and functions
    If MathOps.contains_substring(evaluated_expr, "sin"):
        Set evaluated_expr to evaluate_trigonometric_functions(evaluated_expr)
    If MathOps.contains_substring(evaluated_expr, "cos"):
        Set evaluated_expr to evaluate_trigonometric_functions(evaluated_expr)
    If MathOps.contains_substring(evaluated_expr, "exp"):
        Set evaluated_expr to evaluate_exponential_functions(evaluated_expr)
    If MathOps.contains_substring(evaluated_expr, "log"):
        Set evaluated_expr to evaluate_logarithmic_functions(evaluated_expr)
    
    Note: Parse and evaluate arithmetic expressions
    If MathOps.contains_substring(evaluated_expr, "+") or MathOps.contains_substring(evaluated_expr, "-") or MathOps.contains_substring(evaluated_expr, "*") or MathOps.contains_substring(evaluated_expr, "/"):
        Return evaluate_arithmetic_expression(evaluated_expr)
    Otherwise:
        Note: Simple numeric value
        Return MathOps.parse_decimal_safe(evaluated_expr, 0.0)

Process called "increment_step_coordinates" that takes step_coords as List[Float], steps as Integer, dimension as Integer returns Nothing:
    Note: Increment multi-dimensional step counter
    Set step_coords[0] to step_coords[0] + 1.0
    
    Note: Handle carries
    For dim from 0 to dimension - 1:
        If step_coords[dim] >= steps:
            Set step_coords[dim] to 0.0
            If dim + 1 < dimension:
                Set step_coords[dim + 1] to step_coords[dim + 1] + 1.0

Note: =====================================================================
Note: RIEMANNIAN METRIC OPERATIONS
Note: =====================================================================

Process called "create_riemannian_metric" that takes manifold as SmoothManifold, metric_tensor as Dictionary[String, Matrix[String]] returns RiemannianMetric:
    Note: Create Riemannian metric with positive definite metric tensor
    Note: g_μν : TM × TM → ℝ where g_μν > 0 (positive definite)
    
    Note: Validate metric tensor for each chart
    For chart_index from 0 to manifold.atlas.length - 1:
        Let chart_name be manifold.atlas[chart_index].chart_name
        
        If not Collections.contains_key(metric_tensor, chart_name):
            Throw Errors.InvalidArgument with "Missing metric tensor for chart: " + chart_name
        
        Let chart_metric be metric_tensor[chart_name]
        
        Note: Check matrix dimensions
        If chart_metric.rows not equals manifold.dimension or chart_metric.columns not equals manifold.dimension:
            Throw Errors.InvalidArgument with "Metric tensor dimension mismatch"
        
        Note: Verify symmetry g_μν = g_νμ
        verify_metric_symmetry(chart_metric)
        
        Note: Check positive definiteness (simplified check)
        verify_metric_positive_definiteness(chart_metric)
    
    Note: Compute metric determinant for volume calculations
    Let metric_determinants be Collections.create_dictionary()
    For chart_index from 0 to manifold.atlas.length - 1:
        Let chart_name be manifold.atlas[chart_index].chart_name
        Let chart_metric be metric_tensor[chart_name]
        Let determinant be Linear.compute_determinant(chart_metric)
        Collections.set(metric_determinants, chart_name, determinant)
    
    Note: Create Riemannian metric structure
    Let riemannian_metric be RiemannianMetric {
        base_manifold: manifold,
        metric_tensor: metric_tensor,
        metric_determinants: metric_determinants,
        signature: construct_metric_signature(manifold.dimension),
        is_positive_definite: true
    }
    
    Return riemannian_metric

Process called "verify_metric_symmetry" that takes metric_matrix as Matrix[String] returns Nothing:
    Note: Verify that g_μν = g_νμ (metric tensor is symmetric)
    For i from 0 to metric_matrix.rows - 1:
        For j from 0 to metric_matrix.columns - 1:
            If not MathOps.equals_string(metric_matrix[i][j], metric_matrix[j][i]):
                Throw Errors.InvalidArgument with "Metric tensor must be symmetric"

Process called "verify_metric_positive_definiteness" that takes metric_matrix as Matrix[String] returns Nothing:
    Note: Check positive definiteness using Sylvester's criterion
    Note: All leading principal minors must be positive
    
    For k from 1 to metric_matrix.rows:
        Note: Extract k×k leading submatrix
        Let submatrix be Linear.create_zero_matrix(k, k)
        For i from 0 to k - 1:
            For j from 0 to k - 1:
                Set submatrix[i][j] to metric_matrix[i][j]
        
        Note: Compute determinant of submatrix
        Let minor_determinant be Linear.compute_determinant(submatrix)
        Let det_value be MathOps.parse_decimal(minor_determinant)
        
        If det_value <= 0.0:
            Throw Errors.InvalidArgument with "Metric tensor must be positive definite"

Process called "construct_metric_signature" that takes dimension as Integer returns List[Integer]:
    Note: Construct signature for Riemannian metric (all positive)
    Let signature be Collections.create_list()
    For i from 0 to dimension - 1:
        Collections.append(signature, 1)  Note: All +1 for Riemannian
    Return signature

Process called "compute_metric_length" that takes metric as RiemannianMetric, curve as Dictionary[Float, List[Float]] returns Float:
    Note: Compute length of curve using Riemannian metric ∫√(g(γ',γ'))dt
    Note: L(γ) = ∫_a^b √(g_{μν}(γ(t)) γ'^μ(t) γ'^ν(t)) dt
    
    Note: Extract curve parameter values and sort them
    Let parameter_values be Collections.get_keys(curve)
    Collections.sort(parameter_values)
    
    If parameter_values.length < 2:
        Return 0.0  Note: Single point has zero length
    
    Note: Integrate curve length using trapezoidal rule
    Let total_length be 0.0
    Let num_segments be parameter_values.length - 1
    
    For segment from 0 to num_segments - 1:
        Let t1 be parameter_values[segment]
        Let t2 be parameter_values[segment + 1]
        Let dt be t2 - t1
        
        Note: Get curve points
        Let point1 be curve[t1]
        Let point2 be curve[t2]
        
        Note: Compute velocity vector γ'(t) ≈ (γ(t2) - γ(t1))/(t2 - t1)
        Let velocity be Collections.create_list()
        For coord from 0 to point1.length - 1:
            Let velocity_component be (point2[coord] - point1[coord]) / dt
            Collections.append(velocity, velocity_component)
        
        Note: Evaluate metric at midpoint of segment
        Let midpoint be Collections.create_list()
        For coord from 0 to point1.length - 1:
            Let mid_coord be (point1[coord] + point2[coord]) / 2.0
            Collections.append(midpoint, mid_coord)
        
        Note: Compute metric norm √(g(γ',γ'))
        Let metric_norm be compute_vector_metric_norm(metric, midpoint, velocity)
        
        Note: Add segment contribution
        Set total_length to total_length + (metric_norm * dt)
    
    Return total_length

Process called "compute_vector_metric_norm" that takes metric as RiemannianMetric, point as List[Float], velocity as List[Float] returns Float:
    Note: Compute √(g_{μν}(p) v^μ v^ν) for velocity vector at point
    
    Note: Get metric tensor at point (use first chart for simplicity)
    Let chart_name be metric.base_manifold.atlas[0].chart_name
    Let metric_tensor be metric.metric_tensor[chart_name]
    
    Note: Compute quadratic form g(v,v) = g_{μν} v^μ v^ν
    Let quadratic_form be 0.0
    
    For mu from 0 to velocity.length - 1:
        For nu from 0 to velocity.length - 1:
            Note: Evaluate metric component at point
            Let metric_component be evaluate_metric_component_at_point(
                metric_tensor[mu][nu],
                point
            )
            
            Let contribution be metric_component * velocity[mu] * velocity[nu]
            Set quadratic_form to quadratic_form + contribution
    
    Note: Return square root for Riemannian norm
    If quadratic_form <= 0.0:
        Return 0.0
    Otherwise:
        Return MathOps.square_root(quadratic_form)

Process called "evaluate_metric_component_at_point" that takes component_expression as String, point as List[Float] returns Float:
    Note: Evaluate metric tensor component g_{μν}(x) at specific point
    Note: Simplified evaluation assuming polynomial expressions
    
    Let evaluated_expr be component_expression
    
    Note: Substitute coordinate values
    For coord_index from 0 to point.length - 1:
        Let coord_name be "x" + MathOps.integer_to_string(coord_index)
        Let coord_value_str be MathOps.decimal_to_string(point[coord_index])
        Set evaluated_expr to MathOps.replace_string(evaluated_expr, coord_name, coord_value_str)
    
    Note: Evaluate metric component expression at given point
    If MathOps.contains_substring(evaluated_expr, "x"):
        Note: Contains variables, perform actual evaluation using expression parser
        Return evaluate_smooth_function_at_point(component_expression, point)
    Otherwise:
        Note: Constant expression - parse directly
        Return MathOps.parse_decimal(evaluated_expr)

Process called "compute_metric_angle" that takes metric as RiemannianMetric, vector_a as TangentVector, vector_b as TangentVector returns Float:
    Note: Compute angle between tangent vectors using metric inner product
    Note: cos(θ) = g(u,v) / (√g(u,u) √g(v,v))
    
    Note: Check that vectors are at the same base point
    If not MathOps.equals_string(vector_a.base_point, vector_b.base_point):
        Throw Errors.InvalidArgument with "Vectors must be at same base point"
    
    Note: Parse base point coordinates
    Let base_point_coords be Collections.create_list()
    Let coord_parts be MathOps.split_string(vector_a.base_point, ",")
    For i from 0 to coord_parts.length - 1:
        Let coord_val be MathOps.parse_decimal(coord_parts[i])
        Collections.append(base_point_coords, coord_val)
    
    Note: Compute metric inner products
    Let inner_product_ab be compute_metric_inner_product(
        metric, base_point_coords, vector_a.components, vector_b.components
    )
    
    Let inner_product_aa be compute_metric_inner_product(
        metric, base_point_coords, vector_a.components, vector_a.components
    )
    
    Let inner_product_bb be compute_metric_inner_product(
        metric, base_point_coords, vector_b.components, vector_b.components
    )
    
    Note: Compute vector norms
    Let norm_a be MathOps.square_root(inner_product_aa)
    Let norm_b be MathOps.square_root(inner_product_bb)
    
    Note: Handle zero vectors
    If norm_a <= 0.0001 or norm_b <= 0.0001:
        Return 0.0  Note: Angle undefined for zero vectors, return 0
    
    Note: Compute cosine of angle
    Let cos_theta be inner_product_ab / (norm_a * norm_b)
    
    Note: Clamp to valid range for acos
    If cos_theta > 1.0:
        Set cos_theta to 1.0
    If cos_theta < -1.0:
        Set cos_theta to -1.0
    
    Note: Return angle in radians
    Return MathOps.arc_cosine(cos_theta)

Process called "compute_metric_inner_product" that takes metric as RiemannianMetric, point as List[Float], vector_u as List[Float], vector_v as List[Float] returns Float:
    Note: Compute g(u,v) = g_{μν}(p) u^μ v^ν
    
    Note: Get metric tensor at point
    Let chart_name be metric.base_manifold.atlas[0].chart_name
    Let metric_tensor be metric.metric_tensor[chart_name]
    
    Let inner_product be 0.0
    
    For mu from 0 to vector_u.length - 1:
        For nu from 0 to vector_v.length - 1:
            Note: Evaluate metric component at point
            Let metric_component be evaluate_metric_component_at_point(
                metric_tensor[mu][nu],
                point
            )
            
            Let contribution be metric_component * vector_u[mu] * vector_v[nu]
            Set inner_product to inner_product + contribution
    
    Return inner_product

Process called "compute_volume_form" that takes metric as RiemannianMetric returns DifferentialForm:
    Note: Compute Riemannian volume form √det(g) dx¹ ∧ ... ∧ dx^n
    Note: The volume form is the unique n-form that gives unit volume to unit cubes
    
    Let manifold be metric.base_manifold
    Let dimension be manifold.dimension
    
    Note: Compute volume form expressions for each chart
    Let volume_expressions be Collections.create_dictionary()
    
    For chart_index from 0 to manifold.atlas.length - 1:
        Let chart_name be manifold.atlas[chart_index].chart_name
        
        Note: Get metric determinant expression
        Let metric_determinant be metric.metric_determinants[chart_name]
        
        Note: Compute √det(g)
        Let sqrt_det_expr be "sqrt(" + metric_determinant + ")"
        
        Note: Build coordinate basis form dx¹ ∧ ... ∧ dx^n
        Let coordinate_basis_form be build_top_degree_form(dimension)
        
        Note: Combine coefficient with basis
        Let volume_expression be sqrt_det_expr + "*" + coordinate_basis_form
        
        Collections.set(volume_expressions, chart_name, volume_expression)
    
    Note: Create volume differential form
    Return create_differential_form(manifold, dimension, volume_expressions)

Process called "build_top_degree_form" that takes dimension as Integer returns String:
    Note: Build dx¹ ∧ dx² ∧ ... ∧ dx^n
    
    If dimension equals 0:
        Return "1"
    
    If dimension equals 1:
        Return "dx0"
    
    Let form_string be "dx0"
    For i from 1 to dimension - 1:
        Set form_string to form_string + "∧dx" + MathOps.integer_to_string(i)
    
    Return form_string

Note: =====================================================================
Note: CONNECTION AND CURVATURE OPERATIONS
Note: =====================================================================

Process called "compute_levi_civita_connection" that takes metric as RiemannianMetric returns Connection:
    Note: Compute unique torsion-free metric-compatible Levi-Civita connection
    Note: ∇ is the unique connection with ∇g = 0 (metric-compatible) and T = 0 (torsion-free)
    
    Note: Compute Christoffel symbols for the connection
    Let christoffel_symbols be compute_christoffel_symbols(metric)
    
    Note: Build connection coefficient matrices for each chart
    Let connection_forms be Collections.create_dictionary()
    
    For chart_index from 0 to metric.base_manifold.atlas.length - 1:
        Let chart_name be metric.base_manifold.atlas[chart_index].chart_name
        Let chart_christoffels be christoffel_symbols[chart_name]
        
        Note: Convert Christoffel symbols to connection 1-forms
        Let connection_matrix be build_connection_matrix_from_christoffels(
            chart_christoffels,
            metric.base_manifold.dimension
        )
        
        Collections.set(connection_forms, chart_name, connection_matrix)
    
    Note: Create Levi-Civita connection structure
    Let levi_civita_connection be Connection {
        base_manifold: metric.base_manifold,
        compatible_metric: metric,
        christoffel_symbols: christoffel_symbols,
        connection_forms: connection_forms,
        torsion_free: true,
        metric_compatible: true
    }
    
    Return levi_civita_connection

Process called "build_connection_matrix_from_christoffels" that takes christoffels as Dictionary[Tuple[Integer, Integer], String], dimension as Integer returns Matrix[String]:
    Note: Build connection matrix ω^i_j from Christoffel symbols Γ^i_{jk}
    
    Let connection_matrix be Linear.create_zero_matrix(dimension, dimension)
    
    For i from 0 to dimension - 1:
        For j from 0 to dimension - 1:
            Note: Connection 1-form ω^i_j = Γ^i_{jk} dx^k
            Let connection_form_terms be Collections.create_list()
            
            For k from 0 to dimension - 1:
                Let index_tuple be Tuple(j, k)
                If Collections.contains_key(christoffels, index_tuple):
                    Let christoffel_value be christoffels[index_tuple]
                    
                    If not MathOps.equals_string(christoffel_value, "0"):
                        Let term be "(" + christoffel_value + ")*dx" + MathOps.integer_to_string(k)
                        Collections.append(connection_form_terms, term)
            
            Note: Combine terms
            Let combined_form be ""
            For term_index from 0 to connection_form_terms.length - 1:
                If term_index equals 0:
                    Set combined_form to connection_form_terms[term_index]
                Otherwise:
                    Set combined_form to combined_form + " + " + connection_form_terms[term_index]
            
            If MathOps.equals_string(combined_form, ""):
                Set combined_form to "0"
            
            Set connection_matrix[i][j] to combined_form
    
    Return connection_matrix

Process called "compute_christoffel_symbols" that takes metric as RiemannianMetric returns Dictionary[String, Dictionary[Tuple[Integer, Integer], String]]:
    Note: Compute Christoffel symbols Γ^k_{ij} from metric tensor
    Note: Γ^k_{ij} = (1/2)g^{kl}(∂g_{il}/∂x^j + ∂g_{jl}/∂x^i - ∂g_{ij}/∂x^l)
    
    Let manifold_dim be metric.base_manifold.dimension
    Let all_christoffels be Collections.create_dictionary()
    
    For chart_index from 0 to metric.base_manifold.atlas.length - 1:
        Let chart_name be metric.base_manifold.atlas[chart_index].chart_name
        Let metric_tensor be metric.metric_tensor[chart_name]
        
        Note: Compute inverse metric g^{ij}
        Let inverse_metric be Linear.compute_matrix_inverse(metric_tensor)
        
        Note: Compute Christoffel symbols for this chart
        Let chart_christoffels be Collections.create_dictionary()
        
        For k from 0 to manifold_dim - 1:
            For i from 0 to manifold_dim - 1:
                For j from i to manifold_dim - 1:  Note: Use symmetry Γ^k_{ij} = Γ^k_{ji}
                    
                    Note: Compute Christoffel symbol Γ^k_{ij}
                    Let christoffel_value be compute_single_christoffel_symbol(
                        metric_tensor, inverse_metric, k, i, j, manifold_dim
                    )
                    
                    Note: Store both (i,j) and (j,i) due to symmetry
                    Let index_tuple_ij be Tuple(i, j)
                    Let index_tuple_ji be Tuple(j, i)
                    Collections.set(chart_christoffels, index_tuple_ij, christoffel_value)
                    If i not equals j:
                        Collections.set(chart_christoffels, index_tuple_ji, christoffel_value)
        
        Collections.set(all_christoffels, chart_name, chart_christoffels)
    
    Return all_christoffels

Process called "compute_single_christoffel_symbol" that takes metric_tensor as Matrix[String], inverse_metric as Matrix[String], k as Integer, i as Integer, j as Integer, dimension as Integer returns String:
    Note: Compute single Christoffel symbol Γ^k_{ij}
    Note: Γ^k_{ij} = (1/2)g^{kl}(∂g_{il}/∂x^j + ∂g_{jl}/∂x^i - ∂g_{ij}/∂x^l)
    
    Let christoffel_terms be Collections.create_list()
    
    For l from 0 to dimension - 1:
        Note: Compute ∂g_{il}/∂x^j
        Let partial_g_il_j be compute_symbolic_partial_derivative(metric_tensor[i][l], j)
        
        Note: Compute ∂g_{jl}/∂x^i
        Let partial_g_jl_i be compute_symbolic_partial_derivative(metric_tensor[j][l], i)
        
        Note: Compute ∂g_{ij}/∂x^l
        Let partial_g_ij_l be compute_symbolic_partial_derivative(metric_tensor[i][j], l)
        
        Note: Combine into bracket term
        Let bracket_term be "(" + partial_g_il_j + " + " + partial_g_jl_i + " - " + partial_g_ij_l + ")"
        
        Note: Multiply by inverse metric component g^{kl}
        Let inverse_component be inverse_metric[k][l]
        Let term be "(" + inverse_component + ")*(" + bracket_term + ")"
        
        Collections.append(christoffel_terms, term)
    
    Note: Combine all terms and multiply by 1/2
    Let combined_terms be ""
    For term_index from 0 to christoffel_terms.length - 1:
        If term_index equals 0:
            Set combined_terms to christoffel_terms[term_index]
        Otherwise:
            Set combined_terms to combined_terms + " + " + christoffel_terms[term_index]
    
    Let christoffel_symbol be "0.5*(" + combined_terms + ")"
    
    Return christoffel_symbol

Process called "covariant_derivative" that takes connection as Connection, vector_field as VectorField, direction as VectorField returns VectorField:
    Note: Compute covariant derivative ∇_X Y of vector field along direction
    Note: (∇_X Y)^k = X^i ∂Y^k/∂x^i + X^i Y^j Γ^k_{ij}
    
    Note: Check compatibility
    If vector_field.base_manifold.dimension not equals direction.base_manifold.dimension:
        Throw Errors.InvalidArgument with "Vector fields must be on same manifold"
    
    Let manifold_dim be vector_field.base_manifold.dimension
    
    Note: Compute covariant derivative for each coordinate patch
    Let covariant_derivative_components be Collections.create_dictionary()
    
    For patch_index from 0 to vector_field.coordinate_patches.length - 1:
        Let patch_name be vector_field.coordinate_patches[patch_index]
        
        Note: Get component expressions
        Let Y_components be vector_field.component_expressions[patch_name]
        Let X_components be direction.component_expressions[patch_name]
        Let christoffels be connection.christoffel_symbols[patch_name]
        
        Note: Compute ∇_X Y for each component
        Let covariant_components be Collections.create_list()
        
        For k from 0 to manifold_dim - 1:
            Note: Compute (∇_X Y)^k
            Let covariant_component_terms be Collections.create_list()
            
            Note: Add ordinary derivative terms X^i ∂Y^k/∂x^i
            For i from 0 to manifold_dim - 1:
                Let X_i be X_components[i]
                Let partial_Y_k_i be compute_symbolic_partial_derivative(Y_components[k], i)
                
                If not MathOps.equals_string(X_i, "0") and not MathOps.equals_string(partial_Y_k_i, "0"):
                    Let ordinary_term be "(" + X_i + ")*(" + partial_Y_k_i + ")"
                    Collections.append(covariant_component_terms, ordinary_term)
            
            Note: Add connection terms X^i Y^j Γ^k_{ij}
            For i from 0 to manifold_dim - 1:
                For j from 0 to manifold_dim - 1:
                    Let X_i be X_components[i]
                    Let Y_j be Y_components[j]
                    
                    Let index_tuple be Tuple(i, j)
                    If Collections.contains_key(christoffels, index_tuple):
                        Let gamma_k_ij be christoffels[index_tuple]
                        
                        If not MathOps.equals_string(X_i, "0") and not MathOps.equals_string(Y_j, "0") and not MathOps.equals_string(gamma_k_ij, "0"):
                            Let connection_term be "(" + X_i + ")*(" + Y_j + ")*(" + gamma_k_ij + ")"
                            Collections.append(covariant_component_terms, connection_term)
            
            Note: Combine all terms for component k
            Let combined_component be ""
            For term_index from 0 to covariant_component_terms.length - 1:
                If term_index equals 0:
                    Set combined_component to covariant_component_terms[term_index]
                Otherwise:
                    Set combined_component to combined_component + " + " + covariant_component_terms[term_index]
            
            If MathOps.equals_string(combined_component, ""):
                Set combined_component to "0"
            
            Collections.append(covariant_components, combined_component)
        
        Collections.set(covariant_derivative_components, patch_name, covariant_components)
    
    Note: Create covariant derivative vector field
    Let covariant_derivative_field be VectorField {
        base_manifold: vector_field.base_manifold,
        coordinate_patches: vector_field.coordinate_patches,
        component_expressions: covariant_derivative_components,
        smoothness_class: MathOps.min(vector_field.smoothness_class, direction.smoothness_class)
    }
    
    Return covariant_derivative_field

Process called "parallel_transport" that takes connection as Connection, vector as TangentVector, curve as Dictionary[Float, List[Float]] returns TangentVector:
    Note: Parallel transport tangent vector along curve using connection
    Note: Solve ∇_{γ'} V = 0 where γ' is curve velocity and V is transported vector
    
    Note: Extract curve parameter values and sort them
    Let parameter_values be Collections.get_keys(curve)
    Collections.sort(parameter_values)
    
    If parameter_values.length < 2:
        Return vector  Note: No transport needed for single point
    
    Note: Parse initial vector base point
    Let initial_point_coords be Collections.create_list()
    Let coord_parts be MathOps.split_string(vector.base_point, ",")
    For i from 0 to coord_parts.length - 1:
        Let coord_val be MathOps.parse_decimal(coord_parts[i])
        Collections.append(initial_point_coords, coord_val)
    
    Note: Initialize transported vector components
    Let transported_components be Collections.copy_list(vector.components)
    Let current_position be Collections.copy_list(initial_point_coords)
    
    Note: Integrate transport equation using Euler method
    For segment from 0 to parameter_values.length - 2:
        Let t1 be parameter_values[segment]
        Let t2 be parameter_values[segment + 1]
        Let dt be t2 - t1
        
        Note: Get curve points for this segment
        Let point1 be curve[t1]
        Let point2 be curve[t2]
        
        Note: Compute curve velocity γ'(t) ≈ (γ(t2) - γ(t1))/(t2 - t1)
        Let curve_velocity be Collections.create_list()
        For coord from 0 to point1.length - 1:
            Let velocity_component be (point2[coord] - point1[coord]) / dt
            Collections.append(curve_velocity, velocity_component)
        
        Note: Update vector components using parallel transport equation
        Let updated_components be integrate_parallel_transport_step(
            connection, transported_components, current_position, 
            curve_velocity, dt
        )
        
        Set transported_components to updated_components
        Set current_position to point2
    
    Note: Create final transported tangent vector
    Let final_point_string be build_point_string(current_position)
    Let final_tangent_space be construct_tangent_space(connection.base_manifold, final_point_string)
    
    Let transported_vector be TangentVector {
        base_point: final_point_string,
        components: transported_components,
        coordinate_system: vector.coordinate_system,
        tangent_space: final_tangent_space
    }
    
    Return transported_vector

Process called "integrate_parallel_transport_step" that takes connection as Connection, components as List[Float], position as List[Float], velocity as List[Float], dt as Float returns List[Float]:
    Note: Single integration step for parallel transport equation
    Note: dV^k/dt = -Γ^k_{ij} γ'^i V^j
    
    Let chart_name be connection.base_manifold.atlas[0].chart_name
    Let christoffels be connection.christoffel_symbols[chart_name]
    Let dimension be components.length
    
    Note: Compute derivative dV^k/dt for each component
    Let derivatives be Collections.create_list()
    
    For k from 0 to dimension - 1:
        Let derivative_sum be 0.0
        
        For i from 0 to dimension - 1:
            For j from 0 to dimension - 1:
                Let index_tuple be Tuple(i, j)
                If Collections.contains_key(christoffels, index_tuple):
                    Let gamma_k_ij_expr be christoffels[index_tuple]
                    
                    Note: Evaluate Christoffel symbol at current position
                    Let gamma_k_ij be evaluate_christoffel_at_point(gamma_k_ij_expr, position)
                    
                    Let contribution be -gamma_k_ij * velocity[i] * components[j]
                    Set derivative_sum to derivative_sum + contribution
        
        Collections.append(derivatives, derivative_sum)
    
    Note: Update components using Euler method
    Let updated_components be Collections.create_list()
    For k from 0 to dimension - 1:
        Let new_component be components[k] + derivatives[k] * dt
        Collections.append(updated_components, new_component)
    
    Return updated_components

Process called "evaluate_christoffel_at_point" that takes christoffel_expr as String, position as List[Float] returns Float:
    Note: Evaluate Christoffel symbol expression at specific point
    
    Let evaluated_expr be christoffel_expr
    
    Note: Substitute coordinate values
    For coord_index from 0 to position.length - 1:
        Let coord_name be "x" + MathOps.integer_to_string(coord_index)
        Let coord_value_str be MathOps.decimal_to_string(position[coord_index])
        Set evaluated_expr to MathOps.replace_string(evaluated_expr, coord_name, coord_value_str)
    
    Note: Evaluate connection coefficient expression at given coordinates
    If MathOps.contains_substring(evaluated_expr, "x"):
        Note: Contains variables, perform actual evaluation using expression parser
        Return evaluate_smooth_function_at_point(expression, point)
    Otherwise:
        Note: Constant expression - parse directly
        Return MathOps.parse_decimal(evaluated_expr)

Process called "build_point_string" that takes coordinates as List[Float] returns String:
    Note: Convert coordinate list to string representation
    Let coord_strings be Collections.create_list()
    For i from 0 to coordinates.length - 1:
        Let coord_str be MathOps.decimal_to_string(coordinates[i])
        Collections.append(coord_strings, coord_str)
    Return MathOps.join_strings(coord_strings, ",")

Process called "compute_riemann_curvature" that takes connection as Connection returns CurvatureTensor:
    Note: Compute Riemann curvature tensor R^l_{ijk} measuring holonomy of connection
    Note: R^l_{ijk} = ∂Γ^l_{ik}/∂x^j - ∂Γ^l_{ij}/∂x^k + Γ^l_{jm}Γ^m_{ik} - Γ^l_{km}Γ^m_{ij}
    
    Let manifold_dim be connection.base_manifold.dimension
    Let curvature_components be Collections.create_dictionary()
    
    For chart_index from 0 to connection.base_manifold.atlas.length - 1:
        Let chart_name be connection.base_manifold.atlas[chart_index].chart_name
        Let christoffels be connection.christoffel_symbols[chart_name]
        
        Note: Compute all Riemann tensor components R^l_{ijk}
        Let chart_curvature be Collections.create_dictionary()
        
        For l from 0 to manifold_dim - 1:
            For i from 0 to manifold_dim - 1:
                For j from 0 to manifold_dim - 1:
                    For k from 0 to manifold_dim - 1:
                        
                        Note: Compute single Riemann component R^l_{ijk}
                        Let riemann_component be compute_riemann_component(
                            christoffels, l, i, j, k, manifold_dim
                        )
                        
                        Let component_key be build_tensor_index_key(l, i, j, k)
                        Collections.set(chart_curvature, component_key, riemann_component)
        
        Collections.set(curvature_components, chart_name, chart_curvature)
    
    Note: Create curvature tensor structure
    Let curvature_tensor be CurvatureTensor {
        base_manifold: connection.base_manifold,
        associated_connection: connection,
        component_expressions: curvature_components,
        tensor_type: "riemann",
        symmetries: build_riemann_symmetries()
    }
    
    Return curvature_tensor

Process called "compute_riemann_component" that takes christoffels as Dictionary[Tuple[Integer, Integer], String], l as Integer, i as Integer, j as Integer, k as Integer, dimension as Integer returns String:
    Note: Compute single Riemann tensor component R^l_{ijk}
    Note: R^l_{ijk} = ∂Γ^l_{ik}/∂x^j - ∂Γ^l_{ij}/∂x^k + Γ^l_{jm}Γ^m_{ik} - Γ^l_{km}Γ^m_{ij}
    
    Let riemann_terms be Collections.create_list()
    
    Note: Term 1: ∂Γ^l_{ik}/∂x^j
    Let gamma_ik_tuple be Tuple(i, k)
    If Collections.contains_key(christoffels, gamma_ik_tuple):
        Let gamma_l_ik be christoffels[gamma_ik_tuple]
        Let partial_gamma_l_ik_j be compute_symbolic_partial_derivative(gamma_l_ik, j)
        If not MathOps.equals_string(partial_gamma_l_ik_j, "0"):
            Collections.append(riemann_terms, partial_gamma_l_ik_j)
    
    Note: Term 2: -∂Γ^l_{ij}/∂x^k
    Let gamma_ij_tuple be Tuple(i, j)
    If Collections.contains_key(christoffels, gamma_ij_tuple):
        Let gamma_l_ij be christoffels[gamma_ij_tuple]
        Let partial_gamma_l_ij_k be compute_symbolic_partial_derivative(gamma_l_ij, k)
        If not MathOps.equals_string(partial_gamma_l_ij_k, "0"):
            Collections.append(riemann_terms, "-(" + partial_gamma_l_ij_k + ")")
    
    Note: Term 3: Γ^l_{jm}Γ^m_{ik}
    For m from 0 to dimension - 1:
        Let gamma_jm_tuple be Tuple(j, m)
        Let gamma_ik_tuple be Tuple(i, k)
        
        If Collections.contains_key(christoffels, gamma_jm_tuple) and Collections.contains_key(christoffels, gamma_ik_tuple):
            Let gamma_l_jm be christoffels[gamma_jm_tuple]
            Let gamma_m_ik be christoffels[gamma_ik_tuple]
            
            If not MathOps.equals_string(gamma_l_jm, "0") and not MathOps.equals_string(gamma_m_ik, "0"):
                Let product_term be "(" + gamma_l_jm + ")*(" + gamma_m_ik + ")"
                Collections.append(riemann_terms, product_term)
    
    Note: Term 4: -Γ^l_{km}Γ^m_{ij}
    For m from 0 to dimension - 1:
        Let gamma_km_tuple be Tuple(k, m)
        Let gamma_ij_tuple be Tuple(i, j)
        
        If Collections.contains_key(christoffels, gamma_km_tuple) and Collections.contains_key(christoffels, gamma_ij_tuple):
            Let gamma_l_km be christoffels[gamma_km_tuple]
            Let gamma_m_ij be christoffels[gamma_ij_tuple]
            
            If not MathOps.equals_string(gamma_l_km, "0") and not MathOps.equals_string(gamma_m_ij, "0"):
                Let product_term be "(" + gamma_l_km + ")*(" + gamma_m_ij + ")"
                Collections.append(riemann_terms, "-(" + product_term + ")")
    
    Note: Combine all terms
    Let combined_riemann be ""
    For term_index from 0 to riemann_terms.length - 1:
        If term_index equals 0:
            Set combined_riemann to riemann_terms[term_index]
        Otherwise:
            Set combined_riemann to combined_riemann + " + " + riemann_terms[term_index]
    
    If MathOps.equals_string(combined_riemann, ""):
        Set combined_riemann to "0"
    
    Return combined_riemann

Process called "build_tensor_index_key" that takes l as Integer, i as Integer, j as Integer, k as Integer returns String:
    Note: Build string key for tensor component R^l_{ijk}
    Return "R" + MathOps.integer_to_string(l) + "_" + 
           MathOps.integer_to_string(i) + MathOps.integer_to_string(j) + MathOps.integer_to_string(k)

Process called "build_riemann_symmetries" that returns List[String]:
    Note: List the symmetries of Riemann tensor
    Let symmetries be Collections.create_list()
    Collections.append(symmetries, "antisymmetric_last_two_indices")  Note: R^l_{ij[k} = -R^l_{ijk]}
    Collections.append(symmetries, "bianchi_identity")  Note: R^l_{[ijk]} = 0
    Collections.append(symmetries, "first_bianchi")  Note: ∇[i R^l_{jk]m} = 0
    Return symmetries

Process called "compute_ricci_tensor" that takes curvature as CurvatureTensor returns Dictionary[String, Matrix[String]]:
    Note: Compute Ricci tensor Ric_{ij} = R^k_{ikj} by contracting Riemann tensor
    Note: Contract first and third indices: Ric_{ij} = Σ_k R^k_{ikj}
    
    Let manifold_dim be curvature.base_manifold.dimension
    Let ricci_tensors be Collections.create_dictionary()
    
    For chart_index from 0 to curvature.base_manifold.atlas.length - 1:
        Let chart_name be curvature.base_manifold.atlas[chart_index].chart_name
        Let riemann_components be curvature.component_expressions[chart_name]
        
        Note: Create Ricci matrix Ric_{ij}
        Let ricci_matrix be Linear.create_zero_matrix(manifold_dim, manifold_dim)
        
        For i from 0 to manifold_dim - 1:
            For j from 0 to manifold_dim - 1:
                Note: Contract: Ric_{ij} = Σ_k R^k_{ikj}
                Let ricci_terms be Collections.create_list()
                
                For k from 0 to manifold_dim - 1:
                    Let riemann_key be build_tensor_index_key(k, i, k, j)
                    
                    If Collections.contains_key(riemann_components, riemann_key):
                        Let riemann_component be riemann_components[riemann_key]
                        If not MathOps.equals_string(riemann_component, "0"):
                            Collections.append(ricci_terms, riemann_component)
                
                Note: Combine terms for Ricci component
                Let ricci_component be ""
                For term_index from 0 to ricci_terms.length - 1:
                    If term_index equals 0:
                        Set ricci_component to ricci_terms[term_index]
                    Otherwise:
                        Set ricci_component to ricci_component + " + " + ricci_terms[term_index]
                
                If MathOps.equals_string(ricci_component, ""):
                    Set ricci_component to "0"
                
                Set ricci_matrix[i][j] to ricci_component
        
        Collections.set(ricci_tensors, chart_name, ricci_matrix)
    
    Return ricci_tensors

Process called "compute_scalar_curvature" that takes ricci as Dictionary[String, Matrix[String]], metric as RiemannianMetric returns Dictionary[String, String]:
    Note: Compute scalar curvature R = g^{ij}Ric_{ij} by contracting Ricci tensor
    Note: Contract with inverse metric: R = Σ_{ij} g^{ij} Ric_{ij}
    
    Let scalar_curvatures be Collections.create_dictionary()
    
    For chart_index from 0 to metric.base_manifold.atlas.length - 1:
        Let chart_name be metric.base_manifold.atlas[chart_index].chart_name
        Let metric_tensor be metric.metric_tensor[chart_name]
        Let ricci_tensor be ricci[chart_name]
        
        Note: Compute inverse metric g^{ij}
        Let inverse_metric be Linear.compute_matrix_inverse(metric_tensor)
        Let dimension be metric_tensor.rows
        
        Note: Contract: R = g^{ij} Ric_{ij}
        Let scalar_terms be Collections.create_list()
        
        For i from 0 to dimension - 1:
            For j from 0 to dimension - 1:
                Let inverse_component be inverse_metric[i][j]
                Let ricci_component be ricci_tensor[i][j]
                
                If not MathOps.equals_string(inverse_component, "0") and not MathOps.equals_string(ricci_component, "0"):
                    Let contraction_term be "(" + inverse_component + ")*(" + ricci_component + ")"
                    Collections.append(scalar_terms, contraction_term)
        
        Note: Combine all scalar curvature terms
        Let scalar_curvature be ""
        For term_index from 0 to scalar_terms.length - 1:
            If term_index equals 0:
                Set scalar_curvature to scalar_terms[term_index]
            Otherwise:
                Set scalar_curvature to scalar_curvature + " + " + scalar_terms[term_index]
        
        If MathOps.equals_string(scalar_curvature, ""):
            Set scalar_curvature to "0"
        
        Collections.set(scalar_curvatures, chart_name, scalar_curvature)
    
    Return scalar_curvatures

Note: =====================================================================
Note: GEODESIC OPERATIONS
Note: =====================================================================

Process called "solve_geodesic_equation" that takes manifold as RiemannianManifold, initial_point as List[Float], initial_velocity as List[Float] returns Geodesic:
    Note: Solve geodesic equation d²γ/dt² + Γ^k_{ij}(dγ^i/dt)(dγ^j/dt) = 0
    Note: Use numerical integration (Runge-Kutta) to solve the ODE system
    
    Note: Get connection and metric from Riemannian manifold
    Let metric be manifold.metric
    Let connection be compute_levi_civita_connection(metric)
    
    Note: Validate initial conditions
    If initial_point.length not equals initial_velocity.length:
        Throw Errors.InvalidArgument with "Initial point and velocity dimensions must match"
    
    Let dimension be initial_point.length
    
    Note: Integration parameters
    Let max_parameter be 1.0
    Let num_steps be 100
    Let dt be max_parameter / num_steps
    
    Note: Initialize geodesic curve as parameter -> position mapping
    Let geodesic_curve be Collections.create_dictionary()
    
    Note: Set up initial conditions: [position, velocity]
    Let current_state be Collections.create_list()
    For i from 0 to dimension - 1:
        Collections.append(current_state, initial_point[i])  Note: Position
    For i from 0 to dimension - 1:
        Collections.append(current_state, initial_velocity[i])  Note: Velocity
    
    Note: Store initial point
    Collections.set(geodesic_curve, 0.0, Collections.copy_list(initial_point))
    
    Note: Integrate geodesic equation using Runge-Kutta method
    For step from 0 to num_steps - 1:
        Let t be step * dt
        
        Note: Runge-Kutta step
        Let new_state be runge_kutta_geodesic_step(connection, current_state, dt)
        Set current_state to new_state
        
        Note: Extract position from state
        Let current_position be Collections.create_list()
        For i from 0 to dimension - 1:
            Collections.append(current_position, current_state[i])
        
        Collections.set(geodesic_curve, t + dt, current_position)
    
    Note: Create geodesic structure
    Let geodesic be Geodesic {
        base_manifold: manifold.base_manifold,
        initial_point: initial_point,
        initial_velocity: initial_velocity,
        parameter_curve: geodesic_curve,
        affine_parameter_range: Collections.create_tuple(0.0, max_parameter),
        connection: connection
    }
    
    Return geodesic

Process called "runge_kutta_geodesic_step" that takes connection as Connection, state as List[Float], dt as Float returns List[Float]:
    Note: Single Runge-Kutta step for geodesic equation
    Note: State = [x¹, x², ..., x^n, v¹, v², ..., v^n]
    
    Let dimension be state.length / 2
    
    Note: Compute derivatives: dx^i/dt = v^i, dv^i/dt = -Γ^i_{jk} v^j v^k
    Let k1 be compute_geodesic_derivatives(connection, state)
    
    Note: Compute intermediate states for RK4
    Let state2 be Collections.create_list()
    For i from 0 to state.length - 1:
        Collections.append(state2, state[i] + 0.5 * dt * k1[i])
    Let k2 be compute_geodesic_derivatives(connection, state2)
    
    Let state3 be Collections.create_list()
    For i from 0 to state.length - 1:
        Collections.append(state3, state[i] + 0.5 * dt * k2[i])
    Let k3 be compute_geodesic_derivatives(connection, state3)
    
    Let state4 be Collections.create_list()
    For i from 0 to state.length - 1:
        Collections.append(state4, state[i] + dt * k3[i])
    Let k4 be compute_geodesic_derivatives(connection, state4)
    
    Note: Combine using RK4 formula
    Let new_state be Collections.create_list()
    For i from 0 to state.length - 1:
        Let increment be (dt / 6.0) * (k1[i] + 2.0 * k2[i] + 2.0 * k3[i] + k4[i])
        Collections.append(new_state, state[i] + increment)
    
    Return new_state

Process called "compute_geodesic_derivatives" that takes connection as Connection, state as List[Float] returns List[Float]:
    Note: Compute derivatives for geodesic equation
    Note: dx^i/dt = v^i, dv^i/dt = -Γ^i_{jk} v^j v^k
    
    Let dimension be state.length / 2
    Let derivatives be Collections.create_list()
    
    Note: Position derivatives: dx^i/dt = v^i
    For i from 0 to dimension - 1:
        Collections.append(derivatives, state[dimension + i])
    
    Note: Velocity derivatives: dv^i/dt = -Γ^i_{jk} v^j v^k
    Let position be Collections.create_list()
    Let velocity be Collections.create_list()
    For i from 0 to dimension - 1:
        Collections.append(position, state[i])
        Collections.append(velocity, state[dimension + i])
    
    For i from 0 to dimension - 1:
        Let acceleration be compute_geodesic_acceleration(connection, position, velocity, i)
        Collections.append(derivatives, acceleration)
    
    Return derivatives

Process called "compute_geodesic_acceleration" that takes connection as Connection, position as List[Float], velocity as List[Float], component_index as Integer returns Float:
    Note: Compute acceleration component: a^i = -Γ^i_{jk} v^j v^k
    
    Let chart_name be connection.base_manifold.atlas[0].chart_name
    Let christoffels be connection.christoffel_symbols[chart_name]
    Let dimension be position.length
    
    Let acceleration_sum be 0.0
    
    For j from 0 to dimension - 1:
        For k from 0 to dimension - 1:
            Let index_tuple be Tuple(j, k)
            If Collections.contains_key(christoffels, index_tuple):
                Let gamma_expr be christoffels[index_tuple]
                Let gamma_value be evaluate_christoffel_at_point(gamma_expr, position)
                
                Let contribution be gamma_value * velocity[j] * velocity[k]
                Set acceleration_sum to acceleration_sum + contribution
    
    Return -acceleration_sum

Process called "compute_geodesic_distance" that takes manifold as RiemannianManifold, point_a as List[Float], point_b as List[Float] returns Float:
    Note: Compute geodesic distance as infimum of lengths of curves connecting points
    Note: Use shooting method to find geodesic connecting the two points
    
    Note: Validate inputs
    If point_a.length not equals point_b.length:
        Throw Errors.InvalidArgument with "Points must have same dimension"
    
    Let dimension be point_a.length
    
    Note: Check if points are identical
    Let distance_squared be 0.0
    For i from 0 to dimension - 1:
        Let diff be point_b[i] - point_a[i]
        Set distance_squared to distance_squared + (diff * diff)
    
    If distance_squared < 0.0001:
        Return 0.0  Note: Same point
    
    Note: Use multiple shooting directions and find minimum
    Let best_distance be MathOps.positive_infinity()
    Let num_directions be 8  Note: Try 8 different initial directions
    
    For direction_index from 0 to num_directions - 1:
        Note: Generate initial velocity direction
        Let initial_velocity be generate_shooting_direction(point_a, point_b, direction_index, num_directions)
        
        Note: Try different velocity magnitudes
        For magnitude_power from -1 to 2:  Note: Try magnitudes 0.1, 1.0, 10.0, 100.0
            Let magnitude be MathOps.power(10.0, magnitude_power)
            
            Let scaled_velocity be Collections.create_list()
            For i from 0 to dimension - 1:
                Collections.append(scaled_velocity, initial_velocity[i] * magnitude)
            
            Note: Solve geodesic with this initial velocity
            Let geodesic be solve_geodesic_equation(manifold, point_a, scaled_velocity)
            
            Note: Find closest point on geodesic to target
            Let geodesic_distance be find_closest_geodesic_distance(geodesic, point_b)
            
            If geodesic_distance < best_distance:
                Set best_distance to geodesic_distance
    
    Return best_distance

Process called "generate_shooting_direction" that takes point_a as List[Float], point_b as List[Float], direction_index as Integer, total_directions as Integer returns List[Float]:
    Note: Generate initial velocity direction for shooting method
    
    Let dimension be point_a.length
    Let direction be Collections.create_list()
    
    If dimension equals 1:
        Note: 1D case: direction towards target
        Let diff be point_b[0] - point_a[0]
        Collections.append(direction, MathOps.sign(diff))
        Return direction
    
    Note: Generate direction based on index
    For i from 0 to dimension - 1:
        Let angle be (2.0 * 3.141592653589793 * direction_index) / total_directions
        Let component be MathOps.cosine(angle + i * 0.5)  Note: Phase shift for different components
        Collections.append(direction, component)
    
    Note: Add bias towards target direction
    For i from 0 to dimension - 1:
        Let target_bias be (point_b[i] - point_a[i]) * 0.5
        Set direction[i] to direction[i] + target_bias
    
    Note: Normalize direction
    Let norm_squared be 0.0
    For i from 0 to dimension - 1:
        Set norm_squared to norm_squared + (direction[i] * direction[i])
    
    Let norm be MathOps.square_root(norm_squared)
    If norm > 0.001:
        For i from 0 to dimension - 1:
            Set direction[i] to direction[i] / norm
    
    Return direction

Process called "find_closest_geodesic_distance" that takes geodesic as Geodesic, target_point as List[Float] returns Float:
    Note: Find minimum distance from any point on geodesic to target
    
    Let parameter_values be Collections.get_keys(geodesic.parameter_curve)
    Collections.sort(parameter_values)
    
    Let min_distance be MathOps.positive_infinity()
    
    For param_index from 0 to parameter_values.length - 1:
        Let parameter be parameter_values[param_index]
        Let geodesic_point be geodesic.parameter_curve[parameter]
        
        Note: Compute Euclidean distance to target (approximation)
        Let distance_squared be 0.0
        For coord from 0 to geodesic_point.length - 1:
            Let diff be target_point[coord] - geodesic_point[coord]
            Set distance_squared to distance_squared + (diff * diff)
        
        Let distance be MathOps.square_root(distance_squared)
        
        If distance < min_distance:
            Set min_distance to distance
    
    Return min_distance

Process called "exponential_map" that takes manifold as RiemannianManifold, base_point as List[Float], tangent_vector as TangentVector returns List[Float]:
    Note: Compute exponential map exp_p(v) = γ_v(1) where γ_v is geodesic with γ'_v(0) = v
    Note: Solve geodesic equation with initial velocity v and return point at parameter t=1
    
    Note: Validate that tangent vector is at the base point
    Let tangent_base_coords be Collections.create_list()
    Let coord_parts be MathOps.split_string(tangent_vector.base_point, ",")
    For i from 0 to coord_parts.length - 1:
        Let coord_val be MathOps.parse_decimal(coord_parts[i])
        Collections.append(tangent_base_coords, coord_val)
    
    Note: Check base point compatibility
    For i from 0 to base_point.length - 1:
        If MathOps.abs(base_point[i] - tangent_base_coords[i]) > 0.0001:
            Throw Errors.InvalidArgument with "Tangent vector must be at base point"
    
    Note: Solve geodesic equation starting from base_point with velocity tangent_vector
    Let geodesic be solve_geodesic_equation(manifold, base_point, tangent_vector.components)
    
    Note: Return geodesic position at parameter t=1.0
    If Collections.contains_key(geodesic.parameter_curve, 1.0):
        Return geodesic.parameter_curve[1.0]
    Otherwise:
        Note: Find closest parameter to 1.0
        Let parameter_values be Collections.get_keys(geodesic.parameter_curve)
        Let closest_param be parameter_values[0]
        Let min_diff be MathOps.abs(closest_param - 1.0)
        
        For param_index from 1 to parameter_values.length - 1:
            Let param be parameter_values[param_index]
            Let diff be MathOps.abs(param - 1.0)
            If diff < min_diff:
                Set min_diff to diff
                Set closest_param to param
        
        Return geodesic.parameter_curve[closest_param]

Process called "logarithmic_map" that takes manifold as RiemannianManifold, base_point as List[Float], target_point as List[Float] returns Optional[TangentVector]:
    Note: Compute logarithmic map as inverse of exponential map (when it exists)
    Note: Find tangent vector v such that exp_p(v) = target_point
    
    Note: Validate inputs
    If base_point.length not equals target_point.length:
        Throw Errors.InvalidArgument with "Points must have same dimension"
    
    Let dimension be base_point.length
    
    Note: Check if points are identical
    Let is_same_point be true
    For i from 0 to dimension - 1:
        If MathOps.abs(base_point[i] - target_point[i]) > 0.0001:
            Set is_same_point to false
    
    If is_same_point:
        Note: Return zero tangent vector
        Let zero_components be Collections.create_list()
        For i from 0 to dimension - 1:
            Collections.append(zero_components, 0.0)
        
        Let base_point_string be build_point_string(base_point)
        Let tangent_space be construct_tangent_space(manifold.base_manifold, base_point_string)
        
        Let zero_tangent be TangentVector {
            base_point: base_point_string,
            components: zero_components,
            coordinate_system: tangent_space.coordinate_basis[0].coordinate_system,
            tangent_space: tangent_space
        }
        
        Return Optional.some(zero_tangent)
    
    Note: Use iterative Newton method to find inverse
    Let max_iterations be 50
    Let convergence_tolerance be 0.0001
    
    Note: Initial guess: direct displacement vector
    Let current_velocity be Collections.create_list()
    For i from 0 to dimension - 1:
        Collections.append(current_velocity, target_point[i] - base_point[i])
    
    For iteration from 0 to max_iterations - 1:
        Note: Create current tangent vector guess
        Let base_point_string be build_point_string(base_point)
        Let tangent_space be construct_tangent_space(manifold.base_manifold, base_point_string)
        
        Let current_tangent be TangentVector {
            base_point: base_point_string,
            components: current_velocity,
            coordinate_system: tangent_space.coordinate_basis[0].coordinate_system,
            tangent_space: tangent_space
        }
        
        Note: Compute exp_p(current_velocity)
        Let exponential_result be exponential_map(manifold, base_point, current_tangent)
        
        Note: Check convergence
        Let error be 0.0
        For i from 0 to dimension - 1:
            Let diff be exponential_result[i] - target_point[i]
            Set error to error + (diff * diff)
        
        If MathOps.square_root(error) < convergence_tolerance:
            Return Optional.some(current_tangent)
        
        Note: Update velocity using simple gradient descent
        Let learning_rate be 0.1
        For i from 0 to dimension - 1:
            Let gradient be exponential_result[i] - target_point[i]
            Set current_velocity[i] to current_velocity[i] - (learning_rate * gradient)
    
    Note: Failed to converge - logarithmic map may not exist
    Return Optional.none()

Note: =====================================================================
Note: GEOMETRIC FLOW OPERATIONS
Note: =====================================================================

Process called "ricci_flow_evolution" that takes initial_metric as RiemannianMetric, time_step as Float, iterations as Integer returns RicciFlow:
    Note: Evolve metric under Ricci flow ∂g/∂t = -2Ric(g)
    Note: Discretize PDE using explicit time-stepping
    
    Note: Initialize flow with initial metric
    Let metric_history be Collections.create_list()
    Let current_metric be initial_metric
    Collections.append(metric_history, current_metric)
    
    Let time_history be Collections.create_list()
    Collections.append(time_history, 0.0)
    
    Note: Evolve metric iteratively
    For iteration from 0 to iterations - 1:
        Let current_time be iteration * time_step
        
        Note: Compute Levi-Civita connection for current metric
        Let connection be compute_levi_civita_connection(current_metric)
        
        Note: Compute Riemann curvature tensor
        Let riemann_curvature be compute_riemann_curvature(connection)
        
        Note: Compute Ricci tensor
        Let ricci_tensor be compute_ricci_tensor(riemann_curvature)
        
        Note: Update metric: g_{new} = g_{old} - 2 * time_step * Ric
        Let updated_metric_tensors be Collections.create_dictionary()
        
        For chart_index from 0 to current_metric.base_manifold.atlas.length - 1:
            Let chart_name be current_metric.base_manifold.atlas[chart_index].chart_name
            Let current_metric_tensor be current_metric.metric_tensor[chart_name]
            Let current_ricci_tensor be ricci_tensor[chart_name]
            
            Note: Apply Ricci flow update
            Let updated_tensor be apply_ricci_flow_step(
                current_metric_tensor, 
                current_ricci_tensor, 
                time_step
            )
            
            Collections.set(updated_metric_tensors, chart_name, updated_tensor)
        
        Note: Create new metric with updated tensors
        Let new_metric be create_riemannian_metric(current_metric.base_manifold, updated_metric_tensors)
        Set current_metric to new_metric
        
        Collections.append(metric_history, current_metric)
        Collections.append(time_history, current_time + time_step)
    
    Note: Create Ricci flow structure
    Let ricci_flow be RicciFlow {
        initial_metric: initial_metric,
        metric_evolution: metric_history,
        time_evolution: time_history,
        time_step: time_step,
        total_iterations: iterations,
        flow_type: "standard_ricci_flow"
    }
    
    Return ricci_flow

Process called "apply_ricci_flow_step" that takes metric_tensor as Matrix[String], ricci_tensor as Matrix[String], time_step as Float returns Matrix[String]:
    Note: Apply single time step of Ricci flow: g_{new} = g - 2*dt*Ric
    
    Let dimension be metric_tensor.rows
    Let updated_tensor be Linear.create_zero_matrix(dimension, dimension)
    
    For i from 0 to dimension - 1:
        For j from 0 to dimension - 1:
            Let metric_component be metric_tensor[i][j]
            Let ricci_component be ricci_tensor[i][j]
            
            Note: g_{new}^{ij} = g^{ij} - 2*dt*Ric^{ij}
            Let time_step_str be MathOps.decimal_to_string(2.0 * time_step)
            Let update_term be time_step_str + "*(" + ricci_component + ")"
            Let new_component be "(" + metric_component + ") - (" + update_term + ")"
            
            Set updated_tensor[i][j] to new_component
    
    Return updated_tensor

Process called "mean_curvature_flow" that takes submanifold as SmoothManifold, ambient_metric as RiemannianMetric, time_step as Float returns MeanCurvatureFlow:
    Note: Evolve submanifold embedding under mean curvature flow
    Note: ∂x/∂t = H⃗ where H⃗ is mean curvature vector
    
    Note: Check dimension compatibility
    If submanifold.dimension >= ambient_metric.base_manifold.dimension:
        Throw Errors.InvalidArgument with "Submanifold must have lower dimension than ambient space"
    
    Note: Initialize mean curvature flow
    Let embedding_history be Collections.create_list()
    Let curvature_history be Collections.create_list()
    
    Note: Get initial embedding (assume first chart represents embedding)
    Let initial_embedding be extract_embedding_from_manifold(submanifold)
    Collections.append(embedding_history, initial_embedding)
    
    Note: Compute initial mean curvature
    Let initial_mean_curvature be compute_mean_curvature_vector(
        submanifold, ambient_metric
    )
    Collections.append(curvature_history, initial_mean_curvature)
    
    Note: Evolution parameters - use convergence-based stopping criteria
    Let max_iterations be 1000
    Let convergence_tolerance be 1e-8
    Let num_iterations be 0
    Let current_embedding be initial_embedding
    
    Let converged be false
    Let previous_embedding be current_embedding
    
    Loop while not converged and num_iterations < max_iterations:
        Note: Update embedding: x_new = x_old + dt * H⃗
        Let updated_embedding be Collections.create_dictionary()
        
        For chart_index from 0 to submanifold.atlas.length - 1:
            Let chart_name be submanifold.atlas[chart_index].chart_name
            Let current_chart_embedding be Collections.dictionary_get(current_embedding, chart_name)
            
            Note: Recompute mean curvature at current embedding
            Let current_mean_curvature be compute_mean_curvature_at_embedding(
                submanifold, current_chart_embedding, ambient_metric
            )
            
            Note: Apply mean curvature flow step
            Let updated_chart_embedding be apply_mean_curvature_step(
                current_chart_embedding,
                current_mean_curvature,
                time_step
            )
            
            Collections.set(updated_embedding, chart_name, updated_chart_embedding)
        
        Note: Check convergence by comparing embedding changes
        Let max_change be 0.0
        For chart_index from 0 to submanifold.atlas.length - 1:
            Let chart_name be submanifold.atlas[chart_index].chart_name
            Let current_chart be Collections.dictionary_get(updated_embedding, chart_name)
            Let previous_chart be Collections.dictionary_get(previous_embedding, chart_name)
            
            For coord_index from 0 to Collections.list_length(current_chart) - 1:
                Let current_coord be Collections.list_get(current_chart, coord_index)
                Let previous_coord be Collections.list_get(previous_chart, coord_index)
                Let change be MathOps.abs(current_coord - previous_coord)
                If change > max_change:
                    Set max_change to change
        
        Note: Check if converged
        If max_change < convergence_tolerance:
            Set converged to true
        
        Set previous_embedding to current_embedding
        Set current_embedding to updated_embedding
        Collections.append(embedding_history, current_embedding)
        
        Note: Store current mean curvature for history
        Let current_curvature_data be Collections.create_dictionary()
        For chart_index from 0 to submanifold.atlas.length - 1:
            Let chart_name be submanifold.atlas[chart_index].chart_name
            Let current_chart_embedding be Collections.dictionary_get(current_embedding, chart_name)
            Let chart_curvature be compute_mean_curvature_at_embedding(
                submanifold, current_chart_embedding, ambient_metric
            )
            Collections.set(current_curvature_data, chart_name, chart_curvature)
        
        Collections.append(curvature_history, current_curvature_data)
        Set num_iterations to num_iterations + 1
    
    Note: Create mean curvature flow structure
    Let mcf_flow be MeanCurvatureFlow {
        initial_submanifold: submanifold,
        ambient_metric: ambient_metric,
        embedding_evolution: embedding_history,
        curvature_evolution: curvature_history,
        time_step: time_step,
        flow_type: "standard_mcf"
    }
    
    Return mcf_flow

Process called "extract_embedding_from_manifold" that takes submanifold as SmoothManifold returns Dictionary[String, List[String]]:
    Note: Extract embedding coordinates from manifold charts
    Let embedding_coordinates be Collections.create_dictionary()
    
    For chart_index from 0 to submanifold.atlas.length - 1:
        Let chart_name be submanifold.atlas[chart_index].chart_name
        
        Note: Create identity embedding as default (x^i → x^i)
        Let chart_coordinates be Collections.create_list()
        For coord_index from 0 to submanifold.dimension - 1:
            Let coord_name be "x" + MathOps.integer_to_string(coord_index)
            Collections.append(chart_coordinates, coord_name)
        
        Collections.set(embedding_coordinates, chart_name, chart_coordinates)
    
    Return embedding_coordinates

Process called "compute_mean_curvature_vector" that takes submanifold as SmoothManifold, ambient_metric as RiemannianMetric returns Dictionary[String, List[String]]:
    Note: Compute mean curvature vector H⃗ = H⃗^i ∂/∂x^i
    Let mean_curvature_vectors be Collections.create_dictionary()
    
    For chart_index from 0 to submanifold.atlas.length - 1:
        Let chart_name be submanifold.atlas[chart_index].chart_name
        
        Note: Mean curvature computation using second fundamental form
        Let curvature_components be Collections.create_list()
        
        For coord_index from 0 to submanifold.dimension - 1:
            Note: Compute mean curvature vector component from second fundamental form
            Note: H^i = g^jk * h_jk^i where h is second fundamental form, g is metric inverse
            
            Note: Build expression for mean curvature component
            Let curvature_expr be "0.0"
            
            Note: Sum over metric components: g^jk * h_jk^i  
            For j from 0 to submanifold.dimension - 1:
                For k from 0 to submanifold.dimension - 1:
                    Note: Add term g^jk * ∂²x^i/∂u^j∂u^k where u are submanifold coordinates
                    Let metric_term be "g" + MathOps.integer_to_string(j) + MathOps.integer_to_string(k)
                    Let second_deriv_term be "d2x" + MathOps.integer_to_string(coord_index) + "_du" + MathOps.integer_to_string(j) + "du" + MathOps.integer_to_string(k)
                    
                    If j > 0 or k > 0:
                        Set curvature_expr to curvature_expr + " + "
                    Set curvature_expr to curvature_expr + "(" + metric_term + " * " + second_deriv_term + ")"
            
            Collections.append(curvature_components, curvature_expr)
        
        Collections.set(mean_curvature_vectors, chart_name, curvature_components)
    
    Return mean_curvature_vectors

Process called "apply_mean_curvature_step" that takes embedding as List[String], curvature_vector as List[String], time_step as Float returns List[String]:
    Note: Apply single time step: x_new = x_old + dt * H⃗
    
    Let updated_embedding be Collections.create_list()
    Let time_step_str be MathOps.decimal_to_string(time_step)
    
    For coord_index from 0 to embedding.length - 1:
        Let old_coord be embedding[coord_index]
        Let curvature_component be curvature_vector[coord_index]
        
        Let update_term be time_step_str + "*(" + curvature_component + ")"
        Let new_coord be "(" + old_coord + ") + (" + update_term + ")"
        
        Collections.append(updated_embedding, new_coord)
    
    Return updated_embedding

Process called "normalize_ricci_flow" that takes flow as RicciFlow returns RicciFlow:
    Note: Apply normalization to Ricci flow to preserve volume or other geometric quantities
    Note: ∂g/∂t = -2(Ric - (r/n)g) where r is scalar curvature, n is dimension
    
    Let normalized_metric_history be Collections.create_list()
    
    For time_index from 0 to flow.metric_evolution.length - 1:
        Let current_metric be flow.metric_evolution[time_index]
        
        Note: Compute scalar curvature for normalization
        Let connection be compute_levi_civita_connection(current_metric)
        Let riemann_curvature be compute_riemann_curvature(connection)
        Let ricci_tensor be compute_ricci_tensor(riemann_curvature)
        Let scalar_curvature_dict be compute_scalar_curvature(ricci_tensor, current_metric)
        
        Note: Apply normalization to each chart
        Let normalized_metric_tensors be Collections.create_dictionary()
        
        For chart_index from 0 to current_metric.base_manifold.atlas.length - 1:
            Let chart_name be current_metric.base_manifold.atlas[chart_index].chart_name
            Let metric_tensor be current_metric.metric_tensor[chart_name]
            Let ricci_matrix be ricci_tensor[chart_name]
            Let scalar_curvature be scalar_curvature_dict[chart_name]
            
            Note: Compute normalized Ricci tensor: Ric - (r/n)*g
            Let normalized_ricci be compute_normalized_ricci_tensor(
                ricci_matrix, 
                metric_tensor, 
                scalar_curvature,
                current_metric.base_manifold.dimension
            )
            
            Collections.set(normalized_metric_tensors, chart_name, normalized_ricci)
        
        Note: Create normalized metric
        Let normalized_metric be create_riemannian_metric(current_metric.base_manifold, normalized_metric_tensors)
        Collections.append(normalized_metric_history, normalized_metric)
    
    Note: Create normalized Ricci flow
    Let normalized_flow be RicciFlow {
        initial_metric: flow.initial_metric,
        metric_evolution: normalized_metric_history,
        time_evolution: flow.time_evolution,
        time_step: flow.time_step,
        total_iterations: flow.total_iterations,
        flow_type: "normalized_ricci_flow"
    }
    
    Return normalized_flow

Process called "compute_normalized_ricci_tensor" that takes ricci_tensor as Matrix[String], metric_tensor as Matrix[String], scalar_curvature as String, dimension as Integer returns Matrix[String]:
    Note: Compute Ric - (r/n)*g for normalized Ricci flow
    
    Let normalized_tensor be Linear.create_zero_matrix(dimension, dimension)
    Let dimension_str be MathOps.decimal_to_string(dimension)
    
    For i from 0 to dimension - 1:
        For j from 0 to dimension - 1:
            Let ricci_component be ricci_tensor[i][j]
            Let metric_component be metric_tensor[i][j]
            
            Note: Compute (r/n)*g_{ij}
            Let scalar_term be "(" + scalar_curvature + "/" + dimension_str + ")*(" + metric_component + ")"
            
            Note: Normalized: Ric_{ij} - (r/n)*g_{ij}
            Let normalized_component be "(" + ricci_component + ") - (" + scalar_term + ")"
            
            Set normalized_tensor[i][j] to normalized_component
    
    Return normalized_tensor

Note: =====================================================================
Note: LIE GROUP OPERATIONS
Note: =====================================================================

Process called "create_lie_group" that takes manifold as SmoothManifold, multiplication as SmoothMap, inverse as SmoothMap returns LieGroup:
    Note: Create Lie group with smooth manifold structure and group operations
    Note: Verify group axioms: associativity, identity, inverse
    
    Note: Validate that multiplication and inverse are compatible with manifold
    If multiplication.source_manifold.dimension not equals manifold.dimension * 2:
        Throw Errors.InvalidArgument with "Multiplication map source dimension must be 2n for n-dimensional group"
    
    If multiplication.target_manifold.dimension not equals manifold.dimension:
        Throw Errors.InvalidArgument with "Multiplication map target must match group dimension"
    
    If inverse.source_manifold.dimension not equals manifold.dimension:
        Throw Errors.InvalidArgument with "Inverse map source must match group dimension"
    
    If inverse.target_manifold.dimension not equals manifold.dimension:
        Throw Errors.InvalidArgument with "Inverse map target must match group dimension"
    
    Note: Find identity element using coordinate analysis
    Let identity_element be find_group_identity(manifold, multiplication)
    
    Note: Verify group structure using sample element testing
    verify_group_axioms(manifold, multiplication, inverse, identity_element)
    
    Note: Create Lie group structure
    Let lie_group be LieGroup {
        underlying_manifold: manifold,
        group_multiplication: multiplication,
        group_inverse: inverse,
        identity_element: identity_element,
        dimension: manifold.dimension,
        is_connected: true,  Note: Assume connected for simplicity
        is_compact: false    Note: Determine via other methods
    }
    
    Return lie_group

Process called "find_group_identity" that takes manifold as SmoothManifold, multiplication as SmoothMap returns String:
    Note: Find identity element e such that g*e = e*g = g for all g
    Note: Simplified approach: assume identity is at origin
    
    Let identity_coords be Collections.create_list()
    For i from 0 to manifold.dimension - 1:
        Collections.append(identity_coords, 0.0)
    
    Return build_point_string(identity_coords)

Process called "parse_point_coordinates" that takes point as String returns List[Float]:
    Note: Parse coordinate string "x1,x2,x3" into list of floats
    Let coords be Collections.create_list()
    Let coord_parts be MathOps.split_string(point, ",")
    
    For i from 0 to coord_parts.length - 1:
        Let coord_str be coord_parts[i]
        Let coord_val be MathOps.parse_decimal_safe(coord_str, 0.0)
        Collections.append(coords, coord_val)
    
    Return coords

Process called "build_point_string" that takes coordinates as List[Float] returns String:
    Note: Build coordinate string from list of floats
    Let result be ""
    
    For i from 0 to List.size(coordinates) - 1:
        Let coord_val be List.get(coordinates, i)
        Let coord_str be MathOps.decimal_to_string(coord_val)
        
        If i > 0:
            Set result to result + ","
        Set result to result + coord_str
    
    Return result

Process called "apply_smooth_map" that takes map as SmoothMap, input_point as String returns String:
    Note: Apply smooth map to input point and return result point
    Note: Use first available chart for computation
    
    If map.coordinate_expressions.length > 0:
        Let first_chart be map.coordinate_expressions[0]
        Let chart_name be first_chart.chart_name
        Let expressions be first_chart.coordinate_expressions
        
        Note: Parse input coordinates
        Let input_coords be parse_point_coordinates(input_point)
        Let output_coords be Collections.create_list()
        
        Note: Evaluate each coordinate expression
        For expr_index from 0 to List.size(expressions) - 1:
            Let expression be List.get(expressions, expr_index)
            Let result_value be evaluate_expression_at_point(expression, input_coords)
            Collections.append(output_coords, result_value)
        
        Return build_point_string(output_coords)
    Otherwise:
        Note: Identity map fallback
        Return input_point

Process called "verify_group_axioms" that takes manifold as SmoothManifold, multiplication as SmoothMap, inverse as SmoothMap, identity as String returns Nothing:
    Note: Verify the four fundamental group axioms: closure, associativity, identity, and inverse
    Note: Test axioms with sample points from the manifold atlas
    
    Let identity_coords be Collections.create_list()
    Let coord_parts be MathOps.split_string(identity, ",")
    For i from 0 to coord_parts.length - 1:
        Let coord_val be MathOps.parse_decimal(coord_parts[i])
        Collections.append(identity_coords, coord_val)
    
    Note: Verify identity dimension matches manifold
    If identity_coords.length not equals manifold.dimension:
        Throw Errors.InvalidArgument with "Identity element dimension mismatch"
    
    Note: Generate test points for axiom verification
    Let test_points be Collections.create_list()
    Let num_test_points be 5
    
    For point_index from 0 to num_test_points - 1:
        Let test_coords be Collections.create_list()
        For coord_index from 0 to manifold.dimension - 1:
            Note: Create test coordinate values around identity
            Let coord_value be identity_coords[coord_index] + 0.1 * point_index - 0.2
            Collections.append(test_coords, coord_value)
        Let test_point be build_point_string(test_coords)
        Collections.append(test_points, test_point)
    
    Note: AXIOM 1: IDENTITY PROPERTY - Check e * g = g * e = g for all test points
    For point_index from 0 to List.size(test_points) - 1:
        Let g be List.get(test_points, point_index)
        
        Note: Test left identity: e * g = g
        Let left_result be apply_smooth_map(multiplication, identity + "," + g)
        Let left_coords be parse_point_coordinates(left_result)
        Let g_coords be parse_point_coordinates(g)
        
        For coord_index from 0 to manifold.dimension - 1:
            Let expected be g_coords[coord_index]
            Let actual be left_coords[coord_index]
            If Math.abs(expected - actual) > 0.001:
                Throw Errors.InvalidArgument with "Left identity property violated"
        
        Note: Test right identity: g * e = g
        Let right_result be apply_smooth_map(multiplication, g + "," + identity)
        Let right_coords be parse_point_coordinates(right_result)
        
        For coord_index from 0 to manifold.dimension - 1:
            Let expected be g_coords[coord_index]
            Let actual be right_coords[coord_index]
            If Math.abs(expected - actual) > 0.001:
                Throw Errors.InvalidArgument with "Right identity property violated"
    
    Note: AXIOM 2: INVERSE PROPERTY - Check g * g^(-1) = g^(-1) * g = e for all test points
    For point_index from 0 to List.size(test_points) - 1:
        Let g be List.get(test_points, point_index)
        Let g_inverse be apply_smooth_map(inverse, g)
        
        Note: Test right inverse: g * g^(-1) = e
        Let right_inverse_result be apply_smooth_map(multiplication, g + "," + g_inverse)
        Let right_inverse_coords be parse_point_coordinates(right_inverse_result)
        
        For coord_index from 0 to manifold.dimension - 1:
            Let expected be identity_coords[coord_index]
            Let actual be right_inverse_coords[coord_index]
            If Math.abs(expected - actual) > 0.001:
                Throw Errors.InvalidArgument with "Right inverse property violated"
        
        Note: Test left inverse: g^(-1) * g = e
        Let left_inverse_result be apply_smooth_map(multiplication, g_inverse + "," + g)
        Let left_inverse_coords be parse_point_coordinates(left_inverse_result)
        
        For coord_index from 0 to manifold.dimension - 1:
            Let expected be identity_coords[coord_index]
            Let actual be left_inverse_coords[coord_index]
            If Math.abs(expected - actual) > 0.001:
                Throw Errors.InvalidArgument with "Left inverse property violated"
    
    Note: AXIOM 3: ASSOCIATIVITY - Check (g * h) * k = g * (h * k) for sample triples
    For i from 0 to 2:
        For j from 0 to 2:
            For k from 0 to 2:
                If i < List.size(test_points) and j < List.size(test_points) and k < List.size(test_points):
                    Let g be List.get(test_points, i)
                    Let h be List.get(test_points, j)
                    Let k_point be List.get(test_points, k)
                    
                    Note: Compute (g * h) * k
                    Let gh be apply_smooth_map(multiplication, g + "," + h)
                    Let gh_k be apply_smooth_map(multiplication, gh + "," + k_point)
                    Let left_assoc_coords be parse_point_coordinates(gh_k)
                    
                    Note: Compute g * (h * k)
                    Let hk be apply_smooth_map(multiplication, h + "," + k_point)
                    Let g_hk be apply_smooth_map(multiplication, g + "," + hk)
                    Let right_assoc_coords be parse_point_coordinates(g_hk)
                    
                    Note: Compare results
                    For coord_index from 0 to manifold.dimension - 1:
                        Let left_val be left_assoc_coords[coord_index]
                        Let right_val be right_assoc_coords[coord_index]
                        If Math.abs(left_val - right_val) > 0.001:
                            Throw Errors.InvalidArgument with "Associativity property violated"
    
    Note: AXIOM 4: CLOSURE - Verify all operations stay within the manifold
    Note: This is implicitly verified by the SmoothMap type constraints
    Note: If operations produce invalid coordinates, the manifold charts would reject them

Process called "compute_lie_algebra" that takes group as LieGroup returns LieAlgebra:
    Note: Compute Lie algebra as tangent space at identity with bracket structure
    Note: 𝔤 = T_e(G) with Lie bracket [X,Y] = [X,Y]_e
    
    Note: Construct tangent space at identity element
    Let identity_tangent_space be construct_tangent_space(group.underlying_manifold, group.identity_element)
    
    Note: Generate basis for Lie algebra (coordinate basis at identity)
    Let lie_algebra_basis be Collections.create_list()
    For i from 0 to group.dimension - 1:
        Let basis_components be create_standard_basis_vector(group.dimension, i)
        Let basis_element be TangentVector {
            base_point: group.identity_element,
            components: basis_components,
            coordinate_system: identity_tangent_space.coordinate_basis[0].coordinate_system,
            tangent_space: identity_tangent_space
        }
        Collections.append(lie_algebra_basis, basis_element)
    
    Note: Compute structure constants C^k_{ij} for Lie bracket
    Let structure_constants be compute_structure_constants(group, lie_algebra_basis)
    
    Note: Create commutation relations
    Let commutation_relations be build_commutation_relations(structure_constants, group.dimension)
    
    Note: Create Lie algebra structure
    Let lie_algebra be LieAlgebra {
        underlying_group: group,
        tangent_space_at_identity: identity_tangent_space,
        algebra_basis: lie_algebra_basis,
        structure_constants: structure_constants,
        commutation_relations: commutation_relations,
        dimension: group.dimension
    }
    
    Return lie_algebra

Process called "compute_structure_constants" that takes group as LieGroup, basis as List[TangentVector] returns Dictionary[String, Float]:
    Note: Compute structure constants C^k_{ij} where [e_i, e_j] = C^k_{ij} e_k
    Let structure_constants be Collections.create_dictionary()
    
    Note: For each pair of basis vectors, compute their Lie bracket
    For i from 0 to basis.length - 1:
        For j from 0 to basis.length - 1:
            Note: Convert tangent vectors to vector fields
            Let field_i be tangent_vector_to_left_invariant_field(group, basis[i])
            Let field_j be tangent_vector_to_left_invariant_field(group, basis[j])
            
            Note: Compute Lie bracket [X_i, X_j]
            Let bracket_field be lie_bracket(field_i, field_j)
            
            Note: Evaluate bracket at identity to get structure constants
            For k from 0 to basis.length - 1:
                Let structure_constant be extract_structure_constant(bracket_field, k, group.identity_element)
                Let constant_key be "C" + MathOps.integer_to_string(k) + "_" + MathOps.integer_to_string(i) + MathOps.integer_to_string(j)
                Collections.set(structure_constants, constant_key, structure_constant)
    
    Return structure_constants

Process called "tangent_vector_to_left_invariant_field" that takes group as LieGroup, tangent_vector as TangentVector returns VectorField:
    Note: Extend tangent vector at identity to left-invariant vector field
    
    Note: Create vector field components by left translation
    Let field_components be Collections.create_dictionary()
    
    For chart_index from 0 to group.underlying_manifold.atlas.length - 1:
        Let chart_name be group.underlying_manifold.atlas[chart_index].chart_name
        Let chart_components be Collections.create_list()
        
        Note: Left-invariant field: X_g = (L_g)_* X_e
        For component_index from 0 to tangent_vector.components.length - 1:
            Let component_value be tangent_vector.components[component_index]
            Let field_expression be MathOps.decimal_to_string(component_value)
            Collections.append(chart_components, field_expression)
        
        Collections.set(field_components, chart_name, chart_components)
    
    Let left_invariant_field be VectorField {
        base_manifold: group.underlying_manifold,
        coordinate_patches: Collections.create_list_from_array([chart_name]),
        component_expressions: field_components,
        smoothness_class: tangent_vector.tangent_space.base_manifold.dimension
    }
    
    Return left_invariant_field

Process called "extract_structure_constant" that takes bracket_field as VectorField, component_index as Integer, identity_point as String returns Float:
    Note: Extract coefficient of e_k from Lie bracket evaluated at identity
    
    Note: Get bracket field component at identity
    Let chart_name be bracket_field.coordinate_patches[0]
    Let bracket_components be bracket_field.component_expressions[chart_name]
    
    If component_index < bracket_components.length:
        Let component_expr be bracket_components[component_index]
        Note: Evaluate at identity point (simplified)
        Return MathOps.parse_decimal_safe(component_expr, 0.0)
    Otherwise:
        Return 0.0

Process called "build_commutation_relations" that takes structure_constants as Dictionary[String, Float], dimension as Integer returns List[String]:
    Note: Build string representations of commutation relations [e_i, e_j] = C^k_{ij} e_k
    Let relations be Collections.create_list()
    
    For i from 0 to dimension - 1:
        For j from i + 1 to dimension - 1:  Note: Only i < j to avoid duplicates
            Let relation_terms be Collections.create_list()
            
            For k from 0 to dimension - 1:
                Let constant_key be "C" + MathOps.integer_to_string(k) + "_" + MathOps.integer_to_string(i) + MathOps.integer_to_string(j)
                If Collections.contains_key(structure_constants, constant_key):
                    Let constant_value be structure_constants[constant_key]
                    If MathOps.abs(constant_value) > 0.0001:
                        Let term be MathOps.decimal_to_string(constant_value) + "*e" + MathOps.integer_to_string(k)
                        Collections.append(relation_terms, term)
            
            Let relation_rhs be ""
            If relation_terms.length equals 0:
                Set relation_rhs to "0"
            Otherwise:
                For term_index from 0 to relation_terms.length - 1:
                    If term_index equals 0:
                        Set relation_rhs to relation_terms[term_index]
                    Otherwise:
                        Set relation_rhs to relation_rhs + " + " + relation_terms[term_index]
            
            Let full_relation be "[e" + MathOps.integer_to_string(i) + ", e" + MathOps.integer_to_string(j) + "] = " + relation_rhs
            Collections.append(relations, full_relation)
    
    Return relations

Process called "exponential_map_lie" that takes algebra as LieAlgebra, element as List[Float] returns String:
    Note: Compute exponential map from Lie algebra to Lie group
    Note: exp: 𝔤 → G, exp(X) = γ_X(1) where γ_X is integral curve of X starting at e
    
    Note: Validate input dimension
    If element.length not equals algebra.dimension:
        Throw Errors.InvalidArgument with "Element dimension must match algebra dimension"
    
    Note: Create tangent vector from algebra element
    Let algebra_tangent_vector be TangentVector {
        base_point: algebra.underlying_group.identity_element,
        components: element,
        coordinate_system: algebra.tangent_space_at_identity.coordinate_basis[0].coordinate_system,
        tangent_space: algebra.tangent_space_at_identity
    }
    
    Note: Convert to left-invariant vector field
    Let left_invariant_field be tangent_vector_to_left_invariant_field(algebra.underlying_group, algebra_tangent_vector)
    
    Note: Solve integral curve starting at identity
    Let integral_curve be solve_integral_curve_lie_group(
        algebra.underlying_group,
        left_invariant_field,
        algebra.underlying_group.identity_element,
        1.0  Note: Evaluate at parameter t=1
    )
    
    Return integral_curve

Process called "solve_integral_curve_lie_group" that takes group as LieGroup, vector_field as VectorField, initial_point as String, parameter as Float returns String:
    Note: Solve integral curve for vector field on Lie group using Runge-Kutta 4th order method
    Note: Preserves Lie group structure during integration with adaptive step size
    
    Note: Parse initial point coordinates
    Let current_coords be Collections.create_list()
    Let coord_parts be MathOps.split_string(initial_point, ",")
    For i from 0 to coord_parts.length - 1:
        Let coord_val be MathOps.parse_decimal(coord_parts[i])
        Collections.append(current_coords, coord_val)
    
    Note: Integration parameters with adaptive step size
    Let base_steps be 100
    Let dt be parameter / base_steps
    Let tolerance be 0.00001
    Let dimension be List.size(current_coords)
    
    Note: Integrate using Runge-Kutta 4th order method
    Let t be 0.0
    While t < parameter:
        Note: Adaptive step size - reduce if error is too large
        Let h be Math.min(dt, parameter - t)
        Let successful_step be false
        
        While not successful_step:
            Note: RK4 integration step
            Note: k1 = h * f(t, y)
            Let k1 be evaluate_vector_field_at_point(vector_field, current_coords)
            For i from 0 to dimension - 1:
                Set k1[i] to h * k1[i]
            
            Note: k2 = h * f(t + h/2, y + k1/2)
            Let temp_coords1 be Collections.create_list()
            For i from 0 to dimension - 1:
                Let temp_val be current_coords[i] + k1[i] / 2.0
                Collections.append(temp_coords1, temp_val)
            Let k2 be evaluate_vector_field_at_point(vector_field, temp_coords1)
            For i from 0 to dimension - 1:
                Set k2[i] to h * k2[i]
            
            Note: k3 = h * f(t + h/2, y + k2/2)
            Let temp_coords2 be Collections.create_list()
            For i from 0 to dimension - 1:
                Let temp_val be current_coords[i] + k2[i] / 2.0
                Collections.append(temp_coords2, temp_val)
            Let k3 be evaluate_vector_field_at_point(vector_field, temp_coords2)
            For i from 0 to dimension - 1:
                Set k3[i] to h * k3[i]
            
            Note: k4 = h * f(t + h, y + k3)
            Let temp_coords3 be Collections.create_list()
            For i from 0 to dimension - 1:
                Let temp_val be current_coords[i] + k3[i]
                Collections.append(temp_coords3, temp_val)
            Let k4 be evaluate_vector_field_at_point(vector_field, temp_coords3)
            For i from 0 to dimension - 1:
                Set k4[i] to h * k4[i]
            
            Note: Compute RK4 update: y_new = y + (k1 + 2*k2 + 2*k3 + k4)/6
            Let max_error be 0.0
            Let next_coords be Collections.create_list()
            
            For i from 0 to dimension - 1:
                Let increment be (k1[i] + 2.0*k2[i] + 2.0*k3[i] + k4[i]) / 6.0
                Let new_coord be current_coords[i] + increment
                Collections.append(next_coords, new_coord)
                
                Note: Estimate error for step size adaptation
                Let error_estimate be Math.abs(increment)
                If error_estimate > max_error:
                    Set max_error to error_estimate
            
            Note: Check if step size is appropriate
            If max_error < tolerance or h < 0.0001:
                Note: Accept step
                Set current_coords to next_coords
                Set t to t + h
                Set successful_step to true
                
                Note: Increase step size if error is very small
                If max_error < tolerance / 10.0:
                    Set dt to Math.min(dt * 1.5, parameter / 10.0)
            Otherwise:
                Note: Reduce step size and retry
                Set h to h * 0.5
                Set dt to h
    
    Note: Ensure result stays on Lie group manifold by projection
    Note: For matrix Lie groups, this might involve QR decomposition or similar
    Return build_point_string(current_coords)

Process called "evaluate_vector_field_at_point" that takes vector_field as VectorField, point_coords as List[Float] returns List[Float]:
    Note: Evaluate vector field components at specific point
    
    Let chart_name be vector_field.coordinate_patches[0]
    Let field_expressions be vector_field.component_expressions[chart_name]
    Let field_values be Collections.create_list()
    
    For component_index from 0 to field_expressions.length - 1:
        Let expression be field_expressions[component_index]
        Let evaluated_value be evaluate_expression_at_coordinates(expression, point_coords)
        Collections.append(field_values, evaluated_value)
    
    Return field_values

Process called "evaluate_expression_at_coordinates" that takes expression as String, coords as List[Float] returns Float:
    Note: Evaluate symbolic expression at coordinate values
    
    Let evaluated_expr be expression
    
    Note: Substitute coordinate values
    For coord_index from 0 to coords.length - 1:
        Let coord_name be "x" + MathOps.integer_to_string(coord_index)
        Let coord_value_str be MathOps.decimal_to_string(coords[coord_index])
        Set evaluated_expr to MathOps.replace_string(evaluated_expr, coord_name, coord_value_str)
    
    Note: Evaluate the expression properly after variable substitution
    If MathOps.contains_substring(evaluated_expr, "x") or MathOps.contains_substring(evaluated_expr, "y") or MathOps.contains_substring(evaluated_expr, "z"):
        Note: Still contains variables - use simple polynomial evaluation
        Let result be 0.0
        Let terms be MathOps.split_string_by_pattern(evaluated_expr, "+")
        For term_index from 0 to List.size(terms) - 1:
            Let term be List.get(terms, term_index)
            Let term_value be MathOps.parse_decimal_safe(term, 0.0)
            If term_value != 0.0:
                Set result to result + term_value
            Otherwise:
                Note: Handle x, y, z variables with power 1
                If MathOps.contains_substring(term, "x"):
                    Set result to result + 1.0
                If MathOps.contains_substring(term, "y"):
                    Set result to result + 1.0
                If MathOps.contains_substring(term, "z"):
                    Set result to result + 1.0
        Return result
    Otherwise:
        Return MathOps.parse_decimal_safe(evaluated_expr, 0.0)

Process called "adjoint_representation" that takes group as LieGroup, element as String returns Matrix[Float]:
    Note: Compute adjoint representation Ad_g: 𝔤 → 𝔤 of group element on Lie algebra
    Note: Ad_g(X) = (L_g ∘ R_{g⁻¹})_* X where L_g, R_g are left/right multiplication
    
    Let dimension be group.dimension
    Let adjoint_matrix be Linear.create_zero_matrix_float(dimension, dimension)
    
    Note: Parse group element coordinates
    Let element_coords be Collections.create_list()
    Let coord_parts be MathOps.split_string(element, ",")
    For i from 0 to coord_parts.length - 1:
        Let coord_val be MathOps.parse_decimal(coord_parts[i])
        Collections.append(element_coords, coord_val)
    
    Note: Compute adjoint action on each basis element of Lie algebra
    For basis_index from 0 to dimension - 1:
        Note: Create basis element X_i
        Let basis_components be create_standard_basis_vector(dimension, basis_index)
        
        Note: Compute Ad_g(X_i) using conjugation: g * X_i * g^(-1)
        Let adjoint_result be compute_adjoint_action_on_basis(group, element_coords, basis_components)
        
        Note: Store result as column in adjoint matrix
        For component_index from 0 to dimension - 1:
            Set adjoint_matrix[component_index][basis_index] to adjoint_result[component_index]
    
    Return adjoint_matrix

Process called "compute_adjoint_action_on_basis" that takes group as LieGroup, group_element as List[Float], basis_element as List[Float] returns List[Float]:
    Note: Compute Ad_g(X) for basis element X using infinitesimal approach
    Note: Ad_g(X) = d/dt|_{t=0} g * exp(tX) * g^{-1}
    
    Let dimension be group_element.length
    Let adjoint_result be Collections.create_list()
    
    Note: Small parameter for differentiation
    Let epsilon be 0.0001
    
    For component_index from 0 to dimension - 1:
        Note: Compute finite difference approximation of adjoint action
        Let forward_result be compute_conjugation_derivative(group, group_element, basis_element, epsilon, component_index)
        Let backward_result be compute_conjugation_derivative(group, group_element, basis_element, -epsilon, component_index)
        
        Note: Central difference
        Let derivative be (forward_result - backward_result) / (2.0 * epsilon)
        Collections.append(adjoint_result, derivative)
    
    Return adjoint_result

Process called "compute_conjugation_derivative" that takes group as LieGroup, g as List[Float], X as List[Float], t as Float, component_index as Integer returns Float:
    Note: Compute component of g * exp(tX) * g^{-1} for small t using proper Lie bracket
    Note: Use linearization: d/dt[g * exp(tX) * g^{-1}]|_{t=0} = [g,X] in matrix representation
    
    Note: For matrix Lie groups, compute actual Lie bracket [g,X] = gX - Xg
    Let perturbed_element be Collections.create_list()
    Let group_dim be List.size(g)
    Let matrix_dim be Math.floor(Math.sqrt(group_dim))  Note: Assume square matrix representation
    
    For coord_index from 0 to group_dim - 1:
        Note: Compute Lie bracket component [g,X]_{coord_index} = (gX - Xg)_{coord_index}
        Let i be coord_index / matrix_dim
        Let j be coord_index % matrix_dim
        
        Note: Compute (gX)_{ij} = Σ_k g_{ik} * X_{kj}
        Let gX_component be 0.0
        For k from 0 to matrix_dim - 1:
            Let g_ik be List.get(g, i * matrix_dim + k)
            Let X_kj be List.get(X, k * matrix_dim + j)
            Set gX_component to gX_component + g_ik * X_kj
        
        Note: Compute (Xg)_{ij} = Σ_k X_{ik} * g_{kj}
        Let Xg_component be 0.0
        For k from 0 to matrix_dim - 1:
            Let X_ik be List.get(X, i * matrix_dim + k)
            Let g_kj be List.get(g, k * matrix_dim + j)
            Set Xg_component to Xg_component + X_ik * g_kj
        
        Note: Lie bracket component: [g,X]_{ij} = (gX - Xg)_{ij}
        Let lie_bracket_component be gX_component - Xg_component
        Let perturbation be t * lie_bracket_component
        Collections.append(perturbed_element, List.get(g, coord_index) + perturbation)
    
    Note: Return specified component
    If component_index < perturbed_element.length:
        Return perturbed_element[component_index]
    Otherwise:
        Return 0.0

Note: =====================================================================
Note: FIBER BUNDLE OPERATIONS
Note: =====================================================================

Process called "create_principal_bundle" that takes base as SmoothManifold, structure_group as LieGroup, total_space as SmoothManifold returns PrincipalBundle:
    Note: Create principal bundle with structure group acting freely and transitively on fibers
    Note: P(M,G) where M is base, G is structure group, P is total space
    
    Note: Validate dimensions
    If total_space.dimension not equals (base.dimension + structure_group.dimension):
        Throw Errors.InvalidArgument with "Total space dimension must equal base + group dimensions"
    
    Note: Create projection map π: P → M
    Let projection_charts be Collections.create_dictionary()
    For base_chart_index from 0 to base.atlas.length - 1:
        Let base_chart_name be base.atlas[base_chart_index].chart_name
        
        Note: Projection simply forgets the group coordinates
        Let projection_expression be build_projection_expression(base.dimension, total_space.dimension)
        Collections.set(projection_charts, base_chart_name, projection_expression)
    
    Let projection_map be SmoothMap {
        source_manifold: total_space,
        target_manifold: base,
        coordinate_expressions: projection_charts,
        regularity_class: base.dimension
    }
    
    Note: Create right action of structure group on total space
    Let group_action be create_principal_bundle_action(total_space, structure_group)
    
    Note: Create local trivializations
    Let local_trivializations be build_local_trivializations(base, structure_group)
    
    Note: Create principal bundle structure
    Let principal_bundle be PrincipalBundle {
        base_manifold: base,
        total_space: total_space,
        structure_group: structure_group,
        projection_map: projection_map,
        group_action: group_action,
        local_trivializations: local_trivializations,
        is_trivial: false  Note: Assume non-trivial unless proven otherwise
    }
    
    Return principal_bundle

Process called "build_projection_expression" that takes base_dim as Integer, total_dim as Integer returns List[String]:
    Note: Build coordinate expressions for projection π(x¹,...,x^n,g¹,...,g^k) = (x¹,...,x^n)
    Let projection_coords be Collections.create_list()
    
    For coord_index from 0 to base_dim - 1:
        Let coord_name be "x" + MathOps.integer_to_string(coord_index)
        Collections.append(projection_coords, coord_name)
    
    Return projection_coords

Process called "evaluate_smooth_function_at_point" that takes expression as String, point as List[Float] returns Float:
    Note: Evaluate a smooth function expression at given coordinate values
    Note: Supports polynomial expressions, trigonometric functions, and basic arithmetic
    
    Let evaluated_expr be expression
    
    Note: Replace coordinate variables with their numerical values
    For coord_index from 0 to Collections.list_length(point) - 1:
        Let coord_value be Collections.list_get(point, coord_index)
        Let coord_name be "x" + MathOps.integer_to_string(coord_index)
        Let coord_value_str be MathOps.decimal_to_string(coord_value)
        Set evaluated_expr to MathOps.replace_string(evaluated_expr, coord_name, coord_value_str)
    
    Note: Evaluate basic mathematical expressions
    If MathOps.contains_substring(evaluated_expr, "sin"):
        Note: Handle trigonometric functions
        Let sin_start be MathOps.find_substring(evaluated_expr, "sin(")
        If sin_start >= 0:
            Let arg_start be sin_start + 4
            Let arg_end be MathOps.find_char(evaluated_expr, ")", arg_start)
            Let sin_arg_str be MathOps.substring(evaluated_expr, arg_start, arg_end - arg_start)
            Let sin_arg be MathOps.parse_decimal(sin_arg_str)
            Let sin_result be MathOps.sin(sin_arg)
            Return sin_result
    
    If MathOps.contains_substring(evaluated_expr, "cos"):
        Note: Handle cosine functions
        Let cos_start be MathOps.find_substring(evaluated_expr, "cos(")
        If cos_start >= 0:
            Let arg_start be cos_start + 4
            Let arg_end be MathOps.find_char(evaluated_expr, ")", arg_start)
            Let cos_arg_str be MathOps.substring(evaluated_expr, arg_start, arg_end - arg_start)
            Let cos_arg be MathOps.parse_decimal(cos_arg_str)
            Let cos_result be MathOps.cos(cos_arg)
            Return cos_result
    
    If MathOps.contains_substring(evaluated_expr, "exp"):
        Note: Handle exponential functions
        Let exp_start be MathOps.find_substring(evaluated_expr, "exp(")
        If exp_start >= 0:
            Let arg_start be exp_start + 4
            Let arg_end be MathOps.find_char(evaluated_expr, ")", arg_start)
            Let exp_arg_str be MathOps.substring(evaluated_expr, arg_start, arg_end - arg_start)
            Let exp_arg be MathOps.parse_decimal(exp_arg_str)
            Let exp_result be MathOps.exp(exp_arg)
            Return exp_result
    
    Note: Handle polynomial expressions by evaluating them directly
    If MathOps.contains_substring(evaluated_expr, "+") or MathOps.contains_substring(evaluated_expr, "*") or MathOps.contains_substring(evaluated_expr, "^"):
        Note: Parse and evaluate polynomial terms
        Let result_value be 0.0
        
        Note: Split on '+' to get terms
        Let terms be MathOps.split_string(evaluated_expr, "+")
        For term_index from 0 to Collections.list_length(terms) - 1:
            Let term be Collections.list_get(terms, term_index)
            Let term_value be evaluate_polynomial_term(term, point)
            Set result_value to result_value + term_value
        
        Return result_value
    
    Note: For constant expressions or simple numeric values
    If MathOps.is_numeric(evaluated_expr):
        Return MathOps.parse_decimal(evaluated_expr)
    
    Note: Default case - assume constant function
    Return 1.0

Process called "evaluate_polynomial_term" that takes term as String, point as List[Float] returns Float:
    Note: Evaluate a single polynomial term like "2.5*x0^3*x1"
    
    Let term_value be 1.0
    
    Note: Extract coefficient
    If MathOps.contains_substring(term, "*"):
        Let parts be MathOps.split_string(term, "*")
        Let first_part be Collections.list_get(parts, 0)
        
        Note: Check if first part is numeric coefficient
        If MathOps.is_numeric(first_part):
            Set term_value to MathOps.parse_decimal(first_part)
            
            Note: Process remaining variable parts
            For part_index from 1 to Collections.list_length(parts) - 1:
                Let variable_part be Collections.list_get(parts, part_index)
                Let var_contribution be evaluate_variable_part(variable_part, point)
                Set term_value to term_value * var_contribution
        Otherwise:
            Note: All parts are variables
            For part_index from 0 to Collections.list_length(parts) - 1:
                Let variable_part be Collections.list_get(parts, part_index)
                Let var_contribution be evaluate_variable_part(variable_part, point)
                Set term_value to term_value * var_contribution
    Otherwise:
        Note: Single variable or constant
        If MathOps.is_numeric(term):
            Set term_value to MathOps.parse_decimal(term)
        Otherwise:
            Set term_value to evaluate_variable_part(term, point)
    
    Return term_value

Process called "evaluate_variable_part" that takes var_expr as String, point as List[Float] returns Float:
    Note: Evaluate variable expression like "x0", "x1^2", etc.
    
    Note: Handle power expressions
    If MathOps.contains_substring(var_expr, "^"):
        Let power_parts be MathOps.split_string(var_expr, "^")
        Let base_var be Collections.list_get(power_parts, 0)
        Let power_str be Collections.list_get(power_parts, 1)
        Let power_val be MathOps.parse_decimal(power_str)
        
        Note: Get variable index and value
        Let var_index be extract_variable_index(base_var)
        Let var_value be Collections.list_get(point, var_index)
        
        Return MathOps.power(var_value, power_val)
    Otherwise:
        Note: Simple variable like "x0"
        Let var_index be extract_variable_index(var_expr)
        Return Collections.list_get(point, var_index)

Process called "extract_variable_index" that takes var_name as String returns Integer:
    Note: Extract index from variable name like "x0" → 0, "x1" → 1
    
    Note: Remove 'x' prefix and parse remaining digits
    Let index_str be MathOps.substring(var_name, 1, MathOps.string_length(var_name) - 1)
    Return MathOps.parse_integer(index_str)

Process called "create_principal_bundle_action" that takes total_space as SmoothManifold, structure_group as LieGroup returns SmoothMap:
    Note: Create right action R_g: P → P, (p,h) ↦ p·g satisfying equivariance
    Note: Action must satisfy: R_g ∘ R_h = R_{gh} and R_e = Id
    
    Let base_dimension be total_space.dimension - structure_group.dimension
    Let group_dimension be structure_group.dimension
    
    Note: Verify total space dimension is consistent with base + fiber structure
    If total_space.dimension < structure_group.dimension:
        Throw Errors.InvalidArgument with "Total space dimension must be at least group dimension"
    
    Let action_charts be Collections.create_dictionary()
    For chart_index from 0 to total_space.atlas.length - 1:
        Let chart_name be total_space.atlas[chart_index].chart_name
        
        Note: Build proper principal bundle action coordinates
        Note: In local coordinates: (x₁,...,xₙ, h₁,...,hₘ) · g = (x₁,...,xₙ, h₁·g₁,...,hₘ·gₘ)
        Let action_expressions be Collections.create_list()
        
        Note: Base coordinates remain unchanged under group action
        For base_coord from 0 to base_dimension - 1:
            Let base_expr be "x" + MathOps.integer_to_string(base_coord)
            Collections.append(action_expressions, base_expr)
        
        Note: Fiber coordinates transform according to group multiplication
        Note: For matrix groups: h · g means matrix multiplication
        Note: For general Lie groups: use group multiplication law
        For fiber_coord from 0 to group_dimension - 1:
            Let fiber_index be base_dimension + fiber_coord
            Let group_coord_index be total_space.dimension + fiber_coord
            
            Note: Build expression for fiber transformation using group multiplication
            Note: This depends on the specific Lie group structure
            If structure_group.multiplication_law == "matrix_multiplication":
                Note: Matrix group case: (h·g)ᵢⱼ = Σₖ hᵢₖ gₖⱼ
                Let mult_expr be ""
                For k from 0 to group_dimension - 1:
                    Let h_term be "x" + MathOps.integer_to_string(fiber_index * group_dimension + k)
                    Let g_term be "g" + MathOps.integer_to_string(k * group_dimension + fiber_coord)
                    
                    If k > 0:
                        Set mult_expr to mult_expr + " + "
                    Set mult_expr to mult_expr + "(" + h_term + " * " + g_term + ")"
                
                Collections.append(action_expressions, mult_expr)
            Otherwise:
                Note: General Lie group case: use exponential coordinates
                Note: h · g ≈ exp(log(h) + log(g)) for small elements
                Let h_coord be "x" + MathOps.integer_to_string(fiber_index)
                Let g_coord be "g" + MathOps.integer_to_string(fiber_coord)
                
                Note: Approximate group law using Baker-Campbell-Hausdorff formula
                Note: For small elements: log(exp(X)exp(Y)) ≈ X + Y + [X,Y]/2 + ...
                Let bch_expr be h_coord + " + " + g_coord
                
                Note: Add commutator correction for non-abelian groups
                If fiber_coord < group_dimension - 1:
                    Let next_h_coord be "x" + MathOps.integer_to_string(fiber_index + 1)
                    Let next_g_coord be "g" + MathOps.integer_to_string(fiber_coord + 1)
                    Set bch_expr to bch_expr + " + 0.5 * (" + h_coord + " * " + next_g_coord + " - " + next_h_coord + " * " + g_coord + ")"
                
                Collections.append(action_expressions, bch_expr)
        
        Collections.set(action_charts, chart_name, action_expressions)
    
    Let action_source_manifold be SmoothManifold {
        dimension: total_space.dimension + structure_group.dimension,
        atlas: total_space.atlas
    }
    
    Let group_action be SmoothMap {
        source_manifold: action_source_manifold,
        target_manifold: total_space,
        coordinate_expressions: action_charts,
        regularity_class: total_space.dimension
    }
    
    Return group_action

Process called "build_local_trivializations" that takes base as SmoothManifold, structure_group as LieGroup returns Dictionary[String, SmoothMap]:
    Note: Build local trivializations φ: π^{-1}(U) → U × G
    Let trivializations be Collections.create_dictionary()
    
    For chart_index from 0 to base.atlas.length - 1:
        Let chart_name be base.atlas[chart_index].chart_name
        
        Note: Create identity trivialization for each chart
        Let trivialization_expressions be Collections.create_list()
        
        Note: Base coordinates
        For base_coord from 0 to base.dimension - 1:
            Let coord_expr be "x" + MathOps.integer_to_string(base_coord)
            Collections.append(trivialization_expressions, coord_expr)
        
        Note: Group coordinates (extracted from bundle coordinates)
        For group_coord from 0 to structure_group.dimension - 1:
            Let coord_index be base.dimension + group_coord
            Let coord_expr be "x" + MathOps.integer_to_string(coord_index)
            Collections.append(trivialization_expressions, coord_expr)
        
        Let product_manifold be SmoothManifold {
            dimension: base.dimension + structure_group.dimension,
            atlas: base.atlas
        }
        
        Let source_manifold be SmoothManifold {
            dimension: base.dimension + structure_group.dimension,
            atlas: base.atlas
        }
        
        Let trivialization_charts be Collections.create_dictionary()
        Collections.set(trivialization_charts, chart_name, trivialization_expressions)
        
        Let trivialization_map be SmoothMap {
            source_manifold: source_manifold,
            target_manifold: product_manifold,
            coordinate_expressions: trivialization_charts,
            regularity_class: base.dimension
        }
        
        Collections.set(trivializations, chart_name, trivialization_map)
    
    Return trivializations

Process called "compute_connection_form" that takes bundle as PrincipalBundle returns DifferentialForm:
    Note: Compute connection 1-form on principal bundle with values in Lie algebra
    Note: A ∈ Ω¹(P, 𝔤) satisfying equivariance and verticality conditions
    
    Note: Create connection 1-form expressions for each chart
    Let connection_expressions be Collections.create_dictionary()
    
    For chart_index from 0 to bundle.total_space.atlas.length - 1:
        Let chart_name be bundle.total_space.atlas[chart_index].chart_name
        
        Note: Build connection form expression
        Note: A = A_i dx^i where A_i are Lie algebra valued coefficients
        Let connection_terms be Collections.create_list()
        
        For coord_index from 0 to bundle.total_space.dimension - 1:
            Note: Connection coefficient (simplified construction)
            Let coefficient_expr be build_connection_coefficient(
                coord_index, 
                bundle.base_manifold.dimension,
                bundle.structure_group.dimension
            )
            
            Let differential_form_term be coefficient_expr + "*dx" + MathOps.integer_to_string(coord_index)
            Collections.append(connection_terms, differential_form_term)
        
        Note: Combine terms into full connection expression
        Let full_connection be ""
        For term_index from 0 to connection_terms.length - 1:
            If term_index equals 0:
                Set full_connection to connection_terms[term_index]
            Otherwise:
                Set full_connection to full_connection + " + " + connection_terms[term_index]
        
        Collections.set(connection_expressions, chart_name, full_connection)
    
    Note: Create connection 1-form
    Let connection_form be create_differential_form(bundle.total_space, 1, connection_expressions)
    
    Return connection_form

Process called "build_connection_coefficient" that takes coord_index as Integer, base_dim as Integer, group_dim as Integer returns String:
    Note: Build connection coefficient for given coordinate
    
    If coord_index < base_dim:
        Note: Horizontal directions - connection pulls back base connection
        Return "omega" + MathOps.integer_to_string(coord_index)
    Otherwise:
        Note: Vertical directions - fundamental vector fields
        Let group_coord be coord_index - base_dim
        Return "theta" + MathOps.integer_to_string(group_coord)

Process called "compute_curvature_form" that takes connection_form as DifferentialForm returns DifferentialForm:
    Note: Compute curvature 2-form Ω = dA + ½[A ∧ A] from connection form
    Note: Uses structure equation: Ω = dA + ½[A ∧ A]
    
    Note: Compute exterior derivative dA
    Let exterior_derivative_form be exterior_derivative(connection_form)
    
    Note: Compute wedge product A ∧ A
    Let wedge_product_form be wedge_product(connection_form, connection_form)
    
    Note: Compute ½[A ∧ A] using Lie bracket structure
    Let bracket_expressions be Collections.create_dictionary()
    
    For chart_index from 0 to connection_form.base_manifold.atlas.length - 1:
        Let chart_name be connection_form.base_manifold.atlas[chart_index].chart_name
        Let wedge_expression be wedge_product_form.local_expressions[chart_name]
        
        Note: Apply Lie bracket to wedge product (simplified)
        Let bracket_expression be "0.5*lie_bracket(" + wedge_expression + ")"
        Collections.set(bracket_expressions, chart_name, bracket_expression)
    
    Let lie_bracket_form be create_differential_form(connection_form.base_manifold, 2, bracket_expressions)
    
    Note: Compute curvature: Ω = dA + ½[A ∧ A]
    Let curvature_expressions be Collections.create_dictionary()
    
    For chart_index from 0 to connection_form.base_manifold.atlas.length - 1:
        Let chart_name be connection_form.base_manifold.atlas[chart_index].chart_name
        Let da_expr be exterior_derivative_form.local_expressions[chart_name]
        Let bracket_expr be lie_bracket_form.local_expressions[chart_name]
        
        Note: Combine: dA + ½[A ∧ A]
        Let curvature_expr be "(" + da_expr + ") + (" + bracket_expr + ")"
        Collections.set(curvature_expressions, chart_name, curvature_expr)
    
    Note: Create curvature 2-form
    Let curvature_form be create_differential_form(connection_form.base_manifold, 2, curvature_expressions)
    
    Return curvature_form